<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 93 / Cazenove partner tipped to head Stock Exchange
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The joint senior partner of Cazenove and Company, one of London's most
discreet and successful stockbroking firms, is the leading candidate to
become the next chairman of the Stock Exchange.
Mr John Kemp-Welch, a member of the exchange's board, has been approached by
other board members to fill the post. It is likely to be vacated next year
by Sir Andrew Hugh Smith, who has been chairman since 1988.
'He is clearly the front runner,' said a board member. 'He has indicated
that he is interested, though a formal decision has not been taken either by
him or us.'
Mr Kemp-Welch, who yesterday refused to comment, is due to retire as joint
senior partner of Cazenove on April 30.
Cazenove adopted a unique strategy among leading securities firms when the
stock market was deregulated in 1986 by remaining an independent
partnership. It never publishes financial results, but it is believed to
have been more consistently profitable than any other London securities
firm.
It has about 200 publicly quoted UK companies as clients, including an
unrivalled number of the UK's biggest companies.
Mr Kemp-Welch, 57, who was educated at Winchester, has a reputation for
being tough and single-minded. His father, Mr Peter Kemp-Welch, was also
senior partner of Cazenove.
A member of White's Club in London's St James's, he lists his recreations as
'shooting, farming, cricketing, the hills of Perthshire'.
A board member said that Mr Kemp-Welch was unlikely to commit himself to
taking the post until nearer the time of his departure from Cazenove. He
also pointed out that Sir Andrew had not decided exactly when he wished to
stand down. 'Andrew wants to go in his own time. He wants to make it
abundantly clear that his departure is unconnected to the Taurus debacle,'
the board member said.
Last spring, the exchange cancelled its Taurus project to computerise its
share settlement and registration processes, at a cost to itself and its
member firms of several hundred million pounds. Mr Peter Rawlins, the Stock
Exchange chief executive, took responsibility and resigned.
</TEXT>
