<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The wildlife series made by David Attenborough over the past 15 years,
beginning with Life On Earth, constitute one of the most impressive and
important bodies of work ever undertaken for television. Today brings the
final episode of Life In The Freezer, a series about Antarctica which has
sustained and sometimes surpassed the extraordinarily high standards set by
Attenborough and the BBC's Bristol Natural History Unit in their previous
programmes (8.00 BBC1).
Television has been as influential as any other factor in driving back the
celebration of the winter solstice to the pre-religious roots from which it
sprang. Christmas Time In Vienna is a concert starring Placido Domingo,
Dionne Warwick, and Ruggero Raimondi. Some of their songs may well have
Christian origins, but that seems fortuitous: this is entertainment rather
than an expression of faith (8.00 BBC2).
Word of mouth suggests you should not encourage the children to stay up for
The Secret Adventures Of Tom Thumb which is said to be both'adult' and
occasionally depressing (9.30 BBC2).
