<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 93 / Major sees economic hope and 20p tax
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major talks up Britain's economic prospects in an interview
published today and speaks of his ambition to reduce the basic rate of
income tax to 20p.
The prime minister said in a Daily Telegraph interview there was the
'overwhelming probability' of a long period ahead of stable growth and low
inflation.
He set the long-term objective of nursery schooling for all children,
promised initiatives to improve inner-city education, pledged that the
welfare state was secure and promised that the state pension 'will continue
to maintain its real value'.
Mr Major was optimistic about Britain's economic potential and foresaw the
UK having a far better growth rate than any other European country in the
next two years.
He said it remained the government's ambition to widen the 20p lower band of
income tax until it became the basic rate of tax, replacing the 25p rate.
But the prime minister declined to set a deadline for achieving this.
'We will wait and see. We have to get the deficit down. It depends on what
happens in terms of growth in the economy.'
He foreshadowed a series of government initiatives next year to improve
inner-city education.
These would involve sending in special task forces, or education
associations, to run schools identified by the inspectors as a cause for
serious concern.
Mr Major said that increasingly people would retire with an occupational as
well as a state pension. He denied that the state pension would be a
trifling amount.
'Our commitment is that the state pension continues and it will continue to
maintain its real value,' he said.
'The welfare state is secure. I am not going to move away from the basic
tenets of the welfare state or the social security system.'
</TEXT>
