<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 93 / Women rule the brainwaves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Women have made up the bulk of the recruits who have helped to expand
British universities in the past five years, government figures released
today show, John Authers writes.
Last year women were for the first time more likely than men to move on from
school to higher education. Female participation in full-time and part-time
education outstrips that of males at the ages of both 16 and 17. But
traditional attitudes are still present in the subjects which women study.
Only 1.6 per cent of 18-year-old women attempt A-level physics compared with
6 per cent of 18-year-old men, and more men than women take mathematics.
Business studies A-level is now more popular with women, however. This is
yet to be reflected in industry recruitment, where men are more than twice
as likely as women to be recruited. Among recruits to the teaching
profession there are almost three times as many women as men.
Statistical Bulletin on Women in Post-Compulsory Education. Analytical
services branch, Department for Education. 0325-392683. Free.
</TEXT>
<XX>
