<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 93 / Political Notebook: Return to the real world
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is an important lesson to be learnt from 1993 by those of us
interested in British politics.
The wider electorate does not share the preoccupations and judgments of
Westminster's chattering classes. Yet it is how Mr John Major's policies
play in the country, not in the clubs of SW1, that will determine the future
of his government.
The above may seem an obvious thought but it is too often overlooked even by
sophisticated practitioners of the black art. Take just a few examples from
these two, very separate, worlds of politics during the past 12 months.
During more than half of it politicians and commentators were obsessed by
ratification of the Maastricht treaty. At one dramatic point Mr Major and Mr
Douglas Hurd were set to resign if MPs had voted for something called the
social chapter.
The voters were completely indifferent to such shenanigans, save that they
reinforced their contempt for politicians so distracted from the real world
of economic recession.
More recently there has been Mr Kenneth Clarke's Budget. The combination of
the most draconian spending squeeze for a decade and another hefty round of
tax rises left Conservative MPs howling with delight. Newspaper leader
writers praised it as a masterly political manoeuvre.
And the voters? They hated it. The opinion pollsters could find nobody on
the Clapham omnibus willing to describe the prospects of a cut in take-home
pay, a rise in their heating bills and longer hospital waiting lists as a
'skilful package'. Mr Major's government has yet to pay the price.
Nor is the electorate as stupid as often assumed in the political world of
Westminster. Remember the Newbury by-election back in May. The government
fought it on the basis that economic recovery was under way (technically, it
was).
Weighed down with negative equity and fearful of the dole queues, the voters
were enraged by such presumption. The Conservatives were kicked out. Mr
Norman Lamont followed a few weeks later.
The Christchurch debacle told a similar story. Mr Major said we would hardly
notice value added tax on fuel. Anyway, it was environmentally sound. The
biggest by-election swing against the Conservatives in 50 years provided the
voters' response.
Labour was not immune from flights of fancy. For Mr John Smith the biggest
event of 1993 was his confrontation at the party conference with the trade
unions. It was about something called 'one-member-one-vote', and had to do
with trades unionists selecting Labour candidates.
As the drama was played out in Brighton the more Neanderthal union leaders
said there was a dreadful threat to the historic links between party and
workers.
Mr Smith somehow managed to tell journalists he was determined to break free
from his paymasters while assuring union bosses they would get an even
bigger say under his new system. The row filled the evening news bulletins.
The voters switched channels to Neighbours.
Next year though, it will be different. The two worlds of politics will
converge during the summer when the electorate gets its chance to pass
judgment.
The local elections in May and the European elections in June will provide
the most important test of public opinion during the present parliament.
They will follow hard on the heels of the first tranche of promised tax
rises.
It was the crushing defeats on Mrs Margaret Thatcher's government in the
same elections back in 1989 that started to pull down the curtain on her
premiership.
So the conventional wisdom among the chatterers is that the outcome of next
year's polls will decide if Mr Major stays in 10 Downing Street. This time
they are probably right.
Ministers are already rehearsing arguments to soften the impact of defeat.
The local elections - this time concentrated in the big cities  - will
provide an unreliable guide to sentiment across the country. The European
elections, they add, always have a low turnout. And all governments, of
course, suffer from mid-term blues.
The voters - unlike the pundits - are unlikely to pay much attention to such
excuses. They will see the elections as an opportunity to pass judgment on
Mr Major and his government.
By supporting, or withholding support from, Mr Paddy Ashdown's Liberal
Democrats the electorate will have the chance also to tell us whether Mr
Smith offers a credible alternative. The real world of politics promises a
fascinating 1994.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
