<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 93 / Judge rules SFO can withold papers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Serious Fraud Office should not have to give defence lawyers all
documents covered by widely drafted notices under Section 2 of the Criminal
Justice Act 1988 requiring banks to supply investigators with the relevant
papers, a judge ordered yesterday.
Lawyers for Mr Muhammed Naviede, the former head of the Manchester-based
Arrows trading group who has been accused of fraud, had argued that the SFO
should hand over all documents conceivably covered by the Section 2 notices.
This covered papers not seen by investigators because the banks had not
passed them on.
The situation arose because, under the working of the SFO's Section 2
powers, it is often left to banks to decide which documents are relevant to
a fraud investigation before handing them over. The defence lawyers had
argued that the SFO had 'constructive possession' of documents, if not
physical possession, even if it had decided they were not relevant to its
inquiry.
However, Judge Hawkins QC yesterday ruled that the SFO was not under any
obligation to provide papers in such circumstances.
</TEXT>
