<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 93 / Surprise ruling on pensions bias
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE and VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK company pension schemes can continue to use life expectancy tables which
distinguish between men and women for the purpose of calculating benefits
after an unexpected decision by the European Court of Justice yesterday.
The Luxembourg Court's ruling that European equal-pay rules do not extend to
non-pension benefits, such as tax-free lump sums on retirement and transfer
payments, means UK employers will be able to quantify the main cost
implications of the court's 1990 Barber judgment.
In the Barber case the court ruled that pension benefits of men and women
had to be equalised as they constituted pay for the purposes of the Treaty
of Rome equal-pay rules.
Yesterday's decision was a disappointment for Mr David Neath, whose claim
against his former employer Hugh Steeper, the Leeds artificial-limb
manufacturer, was backed by the Equal Opportunities Commission and the MSF
white-collar union.
Mr Neath was made redundant in 1990 at the age of 54 and was offered the
alternative of a deferred pension or a transfer payment.
He said the company pension scheme discriminated against men by calculating
pensions on the basis that they would be paid at 65, as against 60 for
women, and by using different actuarial assumptions in calculating transfer
payments.
The scheme offered him a pension payable from 65 or a transfer payment of
Pounds 30,672. But if the transfer payment had been calculated by reference
to a retirement age of 60 it would been Pounds 39,934. If female actuarial
factors were also used it would have increased to Pounds 41,486.
The court ruled that these issues were all determined by the funding
arrangements for the pension scheme chosen by the employer and were not
therefore covered by the equal-pay rules.
Mr Robert West, of Hugh Steeper's solicitors Baker &amp; McKenzie, said the
decision resolved one of the few outstanding issues on sex discrimination in
pension schemes and would be welcomed by employers which, contrary to
expectations, would not have to use non-discriminatory life expectancy
tables in future.
The Confederation of British Industry said: 'The possibility of unisex
factors in occupational pensions was causing concern to employers because
they would not reflect the reality of different life expectancies between
the sexes.'
</TEXT>
