<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 93 / Canadian central banker calls time
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Crow, the Bank of Canada governor who has built a reputation as one
of the industrial world's most ardent inflation fighters, said yesterday he
would not be available for another term in office when his first seven-year
term expires next month.
Mr Crow, who is also chairman of the Group of 10 central bank governors,
cited 'personal reasons'.
However, the newly elected Liberal government in Ottawa has been under
strong political pressure not to offer Mr Crow a second term. While foreign
investors and domestic business leaders have strongly backed his
anti-inflation crusade, the Bank of Canada's tight money policies between
1988 and mid-1992 are widely blamed for exacerbating the recent recession.
Mr Crow's position was also undermined by a blunt and condescending manner,
which offended members of the Liberal caucus during their years in
opposition.
He will be replaced by his deputy, Mr Gordon Thiessen. According to one
former Bank of Canada official, the two men's views on economic policy are
virtually identical, but Mr Thiessen has a reputation as a more skilful
communicator. 'Gordon could say the same thing and finesse it,' one former
finance department official said yesterday.
The Canadian dollar initially sank on news of Mr Crow's departure, but
recovered quickly to 74.85 US cents in the early afternoon, half a cent
above its opening level.
Canada's inflation rate has dropped from 5.6 per cent in 1991 to 1.9 per
cent in the year to November. The commercial banks' prime lending rate
reached a peak of 14.75 per cent in mid-1990 but has since tumbled to 5.5
per cent.
The finance minister, Mr Paul Martin, said the government aimed to hold
Canada's annual inflation rate within a 1-3 per cent range until at least
1998. Although he stressed a commitment to containing inflation, the targets
are more flexible than the 'zero inflation' policy favoured by Mr Crow.
</TEXT>
