<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 93 / Sinn Fein told to pick up 'gauntlet of peace': British and
Irish prime ministers strive to regain initiative on Ulster
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN, TIM COONE and Our Belfast Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major and Mr Albert Reynolds tried to recapture the initiative in
their joint attempt to halt 25 years of violence in Northern Ireland
yesterday.
Presenting a united front in statements coinciding with Mr Major's third
visit to the province this year, the British and Irish prime ministers
categorically ruled out negotiations with Sinn Fein until the IRA ends its
armed campaign.
But in a third statement in as many days, Sinn Fein redoubled its efforts to
drive a wedge between London and Dublin, accusing the two governments of
making 'contradictory statements' about last week's Downing Street
Declaration.
The charge from the IRA's political wing came as President Bill Clinton
appeared to offer it an incentive by hinting that he might lift a ban on Mr
Gerry Adams, Sinn Fein president, entering the US in return for a positive
response to the Major-Reynolds initiative.
Mr Major used a surprise visit to Belfast to tell Republican leaders: 'There
is a gauntlet down on the table. It is marked peace. It is there for Sinn
Fein to pick it up.'
He added: "The joint declaration is perfectly clear. There is no need for
fresh negotiations. There is no need for any indecisiveness.'
If Mr Adams wanted clarification, he should stop the violence and wait for a
brief period. Then the questions he wanted answered would be answered.
Accusing Sinn Fein of 'delaying tactics', Mr Major warned that London was
not prepared to wait indefinitely for a positive response to the peace
initiative. 'I don't think one can be strung along for ever,' he said.
On his first official visit to Republican west Belfast, Mr Major urged
listeners: 'Don't play Mr Adams's game. He has an opportunity. That
opportunity is marked peace. The opportunity is on the table - does Mr Adams
have the will and the courage to pick it up?'
Before moving on to meetings last night at Hillsborough with church and
community leaders and leaders of Northern Ireland's four non-violent
political parties, the prime minister said a terrorist decision to renounce
violence was the only 'sane' decision that could be made. The men of
violence no longer had 'a shred of justification'.
Mr Reynolds echoed Mr Major's line in telling the Irish senate the 'next
stage' of negotiations with Sinn Fein could come only after peace 'has first
been established'. But the Irish prime minister took a more emollient tack
in pledging 'an enlightened and pragmatic approach' in subsequent talks on
'difficult' security issues. A 'balanced' approach would be essential, he
said.
In a further hint at flexibility, he said the Republic's broadcasting ban on
Sinn Fein would be reviewed 'in depth' on January 19. Mr Peter Brooke,
national heritage secretary, is expected to report to Mr Major on a review
of similar British restrictions about the same time.
As Mr Adams repeated calls for talks with London and Dublin to clarify
'confusions and contradictions' in the declaration, senior Sinn Fein
officials said 'direct contact' was now 'a vital and essential part of the
process'.
But after a meeting of the party's national executive committee in Dublin,
Mr Caoimnghin O'Caolain, a committee member, said he did not believe the
peace process was deadlocked. Mr O'Caolain also hinted Sinn Fein had tried
to reopen its secret channel of negotiations with the British government.
There was no indication whether the IRA is planning to extend its
traditional three-day Christmas ceasefire, spanning Christmas Eve to Boxing
Day. That is expected today.
Yesterday's developments came after the Irish Times reported that President
Clinton had indicated the ban on Mr Adams entering the US might be lifted.
Observer, Page 11
</TEXT>
<XX>
