<DATELINE>
   YAOUNDE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Cameroon, which has 11.5 per cent of Africa's rainforest with 300 varieties
of trees, adopted a tropical timber trade law yesterday aimed at reducing
foreign domination of the industry, Reuter reports from Yaounde. The
country's timber trade is 80 per cent controlled by expatriates, notably the
French, and the new law aims to increase state revenue. But the French
director of a forestry company said the law would deter reinvestment.
