<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / EU cracks whip over enforcing its laws
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
In a legal assault meant to enforce the European Union's single market, the
European Community said yesterday it would take member countries to court in
184 cases where they have failed to implement EU legislation, AP-DJ reports
from Brussels.
The offensive reverses an 11-month truce between the Commission, which is
responsible for upholding Community rules, and member states which have been
slow to take in Community laws to national legislation.
The Commission said it would file the complaints with the European Court of
Justice, the Community's highest court, against recalcitrant members.
It said it had also decided to open 103 new internal proceedings against the
12 EU governments, and send 709 'reasoned opinions', giving governments two
months to bring national laws into line with EU norms.
Commission spokesmen refused to give details about where the alleged
breaches of legislation have occurred, or even to say which members states
were involved.
In a statement, however, the Commission said the move illustrates a
'co-operative rather than confrontational' approach towards member
countries.
</TEXT>
