<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Survey of Environmental Management (10): Debate rages on
liability / Review of the problem of contaminated land
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Cleaning up contaminated land has emerged as one of the toughest problems in
environmental management.
Developed countries, particularly those such as Britain, with a long
industrial history, have tens of thousands of sites which have been
contaminated over the years with waste and hazardous materials.
Even leaving aside the technical difficulties, the question of who should
pay the enormous costs involved is an important issue for many countries.
Although 'the polluter pays' is the widely adopted principle, it fails to
provide a complete answer because the polluter may be long dead, or
untraceable. And while public opinion may be clamouring for sites to be
cleaned up and the polluter punished, the business community has begun to
fight back because it fears the bill will land on its doorstep.
Earlier this year, the UK government was forced to drop plans for a register
of contaminated land because of opposition from business and property owners
who feared it would have a devastating effect on land values.
The US launched an assault on the problem with its 1980 Comprehensive
Environmental Response Compensation and Liability Act (Cercla), or Superfund
programme. This provides the government with money to clean up sites and
pursue polluters. But although the programme was supposed to prevent
disputes about responsibility from delaying clean-up work, the result has
been rather the opposite. Fewer than 100 sites have been cleaned up - but a
lot of money has been spent on legal argument. The Clinton Administration is
now preparing to re-authorise the Superfund, so the debate about
environmental liability is likely to be revived in the US.
In Europe, the Council of Europe drew up a convention on environmental
liability earlier this year, but several countries (including the UK)
declined to sign it because they thought it too sweeping in scope. The focus
has now switched to a green paper from the European Commission on civil
liability for environmental damage, which has also caused widespread
controversy.
The paper proposes a strict liability regime which would be harmonised
across the community. This would be linked to a compensation plan for cases
where the polluter cannot be identified. The paper has upset a wide swathe
of the business and financial community, which fears that owners of land
could be held responsible for damage caused by previous owners.
Opposition is particularly strong in the UK, which has a different legal
tradition from continental countries. Mr Tim Yeo, the UK's environment
minister, pledged in a recent speech to British bankers that the government
would oppose the directive in its present form. 'No evidence has been
provided to support claims that EU action in this area would deliver any
additional environmental benefits at all in the UK.'
Mr John Garbutt, head of the planning and environment unit at Nicholson
Graham &amp; Jones, a City of London law firm, says: 'It would establish a level
of liability which we don't accept in this country.'
Banks are particularly worried that they could be sued for environmental
damage caused by their borrowers. These fears date back to the late 1980s,
when a US court ruled that a bank could be liable where there was evidence
that it was in a position to influence the way a client disposed of
hazardous waste. Although the Environment Protection Agency subsequently
issued a regulation which annulled this ruling, that action is now being
challenged in the US courts. 'The position is still unsettled,' said a
spokesman for the American Bankers Association, which is urging Congress to
pass fresh legislation to clarify the issue once and for all.
In Brussels the Federation Bancaire, which represents the EU's banks, has
warned the Commission against going down the Superfund route, and has asked
for special exemptions for banks.
Some of the insurance industry's anxiety about pollution claims in the UK
was eased with an important House of Lords ruling earlier this month in the
long running Eastern Counties Leather case. The tanning company had been
found liable by a lower court for polluting the local water supply with a
solvent and told to pay the water company's costs even though the spillages
ceased in 1976 and the applicable EC directive did not require compliance
until 1985.
But the law lords said the tannery could not have 'reasonably foreseen' at
the time that it used the solvent that the spillages would lead to any
environmental hazards. The ruling was widely welcomed because it averted the
danger that the concept of retrospective liability would be introduced into
English law.
Even if the issue of liability can be settled by redrafting appropriate
laws, the question of who should pay, where the original polluter cannot be
traced, remains a heated issue.
Environmentalist organisations such as Greenpeace have put forward proposals
for a special tax on 'dirty' industries which would be used to fund a
clean-up campaign. The EU green paper proposes a compensation fund which
would be financed by a levy on industry. But as Mr Tom Handler of the
international law firm Baker &amp; McKenzie says: 'How do you define the
industries?'
In Germany, which has a special problem with its formerly communist eastern
region, the early purchasers of property there were exempted from liability
for any environmental damage caused by the property in the past.
In the UK, several laws and agencies already address the issue of clean-ups.
But the government is currently conducting a review after the failure of its
contaminated land register plan. The CBI has been arguing that the cost of
cleaning up past pollution should be borne by a partnership of private and
public sector money, but with increased emphasis on state and EU
regeneration grants. However, Mr Yeo was careful in his speech to bankers
not to commit the government to footing the clean-up bill.
'Deciding what the liability should be and where it should fall - on the
polluter, the owner or the state - is not easy. There is no simple solution
and it may be that different provisions should apply in different
situations. However, no one has the right to be regarded as a special case.'
</TEXT>
