<DOCNO>FT934-811</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DLVCCAFYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931222
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Survey of Saudi Arabia (9): The results start to show /
Profile of Sabic's expansion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Seldom can a company have undertaken so ambitious an expansion project into
the teeth of so unpromising a market as Sabic, the kingdom's vast industrial
holding group.
By the end of 1995, according to Mr Ibrahim bin Salamah, Sabic's
vice-chairman and managing director, the 70 per cent state-owned group will
have raised around Dollars 4bn to finance expansion projects at 12 of its 18
subsidiaries or affiliates, aimed at raising total output to 20m tonnes a
year from just over 12m tonnes at the start of the decade.
It is an expansion central to Saudi Arabia's industrial planning. The Sabic
group's family of companies and joint ventures represents the kingdom's
biggest non-oil industrial enterprise, employing 11,000 people. Since its
creation in 1976, it has been the predominant force behind the country's
development of its gas-based petrochemicals potential.
At the same time, however, the world recession has considerably softened
world prices of petrochemicals - Sabic's core market - with resulting damage
to the group's profits. Earlier this year, the group reported a 14 per cent
fall in 1992 earnings to Dollars 523m despite a 20 per cent rise in output
to 15.7m tonnes. Profits for 1991 had, in turn, been 24 per cent down on the
preceding year.
But there are tentative signs that the sheer scale of Sabic's expansion,
combined with the tremendous luxury of cheap gas feedstock it enjoys, is
turning the results around. Although Mr Salamah says profits for the first
nine months of 1993 remain 6 per cent down on the same period last year,
earnings in the third quarter were 10 per cent up on the same three months
last year. 'You can't say it's an improvement in prices,' he says. 'But we
now have more production coming on stream which, combined with our effort to
cut costs, is showing some results.'
He says the group has kept costs level over 1993 so far through efforts to
reduce bottlenecks at plants, cut inventories, improve transport and storage
efficiency and trim marketing costs. However, the group's chief cost
advantage in a weak world market is the fact that it purchases its feedstock
gases from Saudi Aramco, the state oil producer and refiner, at a guaranteed
30 per cent below the price of any competing supplier.
But Mr Salamah says that this apparent subsidy is less than it appears,
arguing that Sabic buys the gas direct from Aramco's gas-oil separation
plants and makes up much of the 30 per cent discount through having to
supply all costs of transport and refrigeration. 'The price is basically a
netback cost from the separation plants, not really a discount as such,' he
says.
By the end of this year, he says, total output of Sabic's mix of chemicals,
plastics, fertilisers, steel and gases will exceed 17m tonnes - around
two-thirds of which will be exported. 'The important thing is to maintain
our market share,' he says - which is currently about 6 per cent of the
world petrochemical market.
Of the 12 expansion projects, five are complete, four are between 80-97 per
cent finished and three are just getting under way. By Sabic's own
reckoning, just three projects are behind schedule.
Among the completed projects, Petrokemya, a wholly-owned affiliate, has
completed expansion of a new olefins plant boosting capacity to 1.8m tonnes
a year from 830,000 t/y. The new flexible feedstock cracker adds 300,000 t/y
of propylene output, 100,000 t/y of butadiene and 70,000 t/y of benzine
output, while raising ethylene capacity by 500,000 t/y to 1.15m t/y.
Propylene from Petrokemya will in turn feed Ibn Zahr, the country's first
polypropylene plant and another Sabic affiliate, which is slightly behind a
target of opening production of 200,000 t/y by the year's end, mostly to
feed local industries and the Gulf. This will see Sabic producing five basic
thermoplastic resins, complementing output of linear low density
polyethylene, high density polyethylene, polystyrene and polyvinyl chloride.
Elsewhere, Hadeed, Sabic's steel subsidiary, has completed expansion to 2.2m
t/y capacity from 1.6m t/y, Safco has also finished a new fertiliser complex
at Jubail to boost capacity in ammonia and urea, while Sharq has doubled
ethylene glycol capacity to 660,000 t/y and has nearly completed work to
boost polyethylene output. Gas, Sabic's air separation affiliate, has
additionally doubled nitrogen and oxygen output to feed other Sabic
industries to 490,000 t/y and 876,000 t/y respectively.
Ibn Hayyan, the majority-held plastics group, is in the early stages of
building a PVC paste plant which is due to come on stream in the last
quarter of next year, while work will begin in two to three months on a new
polyester plant for AIFC, the Sabic subsidiary at Yanbu. The main expansion
projects will be completed with an ethyl-hexanol plant in the early stages
of engineering at Samad, a 50-50 joint venture between Sabic and Taiwan
Fertiliser at Jubail. Both are set to begin production by early 1996 at the
latest.
Sabic is also on the verge of becoming one of the world's biggest producers
of methyl tertiary butyl ethers, the petrol additive which cuts carbon
pollutants while increasing octane. With the completion of new plants at Ibn
Zahr and Ibn Sina, both in the industrial city of Jubail, Mr Salamah
estimates Sabic will be producing 2.8m to 3m tonnes of MTBE a year by 1997.
In addition to this, Sabic has also recently consolidated its research and
development into a single new research centre in Riyadh as part of a
concerted effort to rationalise the group's cost base. Mr Salamah estimates
Sabic's annual R&amp;D budget at SR400m annually.
</TEXT>
