<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Survey of Environmental Management (8): Plans to 'wrap' it
up - The chemicals industry must apply self-interest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Few industrial sectors have an environmental image as appalling as that of
the chemicals industry. In the UK, public approval for the chemicals sector
has declined from more than 50 per cent at the start of the 1980s to less
than 20 per cent last year. The declining popularity of its chemical
companies has been mirrored by that of its counterparts around the globe.
'The chemical sector is rightfully cast among the problem industries,'
concedes Mr Nicholas Reding, vice-chairman of Monsanto, the US chemicals
company.
The dangers of not improving the performance and image of the industry are
serious. 'If the industry fails to clean up its act, it runs the risk of
being legislated out of existence, argues Mr David Buzzelli, director
responsible for the environment at Dow Chemical, the US group.
'Failure to improve both performance and image will be very expensive.
Planning approvals for investment will be refused, making sites uneconomic.
Plants will be driven further from employees and markets, further adding to
costs. The chemicals industry could be legislated to the point of economic
non-viability,' he says.
Mr Mike LaGraff, BP Chemicals manager for health, safety and the
environment, agrees: 'The industry must improve its environmental
performance not because it is being altruistic - although as corporate
citizens we do care. It must improve out of self-interest.'
The industry is being asked to spend ever-increasing amounts to meet
environmentally-related legislation at a time when chemicals groups can
least afford them.
Many chemicals segments are struggling with over-capacity, poor demand
growth, dire operating rates, declining margins and tumbling profits. Some
sectors, such as the European petrochemicals industry, are bleeding red ink
and require restructuring.
Nevertheless, the chemicals industry has spent billions of dollars trying to
clean up its act. Around the globe, the sector is trying polish its
tarnished image and regain public trust through its programme of Responsible
Care.
This involves measuring emissions in a credible way, improving environmental
performance and then communicating that performance, warts and all, to the
public. The programme was initially created by the Canadian chemicals
industry, was adopted by the US, migrated over the Atlantic to Europe, and
has now proliferated worldwide.
Convincing all companies of the value of Responsible Care has not been easy.
But most now accept the need for the programme.
The key to the process is measuring and then improving environmental
performance. 'We don't want to put out propaganda. There is no point
communicating, if you don't have anything of substance to communicate,'
warns Mr Kasper Eigenmann, head of corporate unit safety and environment at
Ciba, the Swiss group.
Over the past decade, most companies have invested heavily in end of pipe
solutions - treating waste after it has been created. Now they are turning
their attention to waste minimisation. Some groups have adopted the concept
as their mantra. Dow, for example, has a programme called Wrap - waste
reduction always pays.
The rhetoric behind Responsible Care is laudable, but implementing the
programme is far from easy. It involves far more than just investing in
technology and plant. Rather, it requires a change in an organisation's very
culture.
'Responsible Care is not just a question of following a set of rules. It's
like driving a car. There are a lot of regulations about how to drive, but
we still have bad drivers. In the same way you can have companies that
comply with regulations, but are not environmentally sound. An integral part
of Responsible Care is a change in culture within the organisation,' says Mr
Jacques Puechal, president of Cefic, the European Council of the Chemical
Industry, and chief executive of Elf-Atochem.
The impact of environmental measures can be dramatic. Take Leverkusen, the
main manufacturing location for Bayer, the leading German industrial group.
The giant chimneys stacked along the Rhine no longer spew smoke and are home
to hawks and other bird-life. The Rhine is sufficiently full of fish to
support a population of storks nearby during the summer.
But to repair its damaged reputation, the chemicals industry must not only
improve its environmental performance; it must also communicate that
improvement in a credible manner. Much of this historically secretive
industry is now trying to become more open in its communications with local
communities and the public.
The issue of credibility is the key. It depends foremost on the quality of
environmental reporting. However, the sector is still divided on the issue.
While some groups, such as BP Chemicals, have taken to publishing all their
emissions, others, such as Ciba and Rhone-Poulenc of France, prefer to
publish indices. Solvay of Belgium published its first set of figures this
month. Others still refuse to publish group figures.
At Monsanto, Mr Reding admits he had worries when the company started
publishing its entire emission figures because they might provide ammunition
for environmental groups. 'In fact, the external reaction has generally been
pretty good, even if we have a long way to go to reduce our emissions,' he
says.
The chemicals industry has made enormous strides in its environmental
performance and reporting. But it must make greater efforts in its
communications if it is to change public attitudes to the sector.
Britain's chemicals industry spent more than Pounds 1bn on the environment
last year, according to figures released by the industry's trade body. That
represents about 3 per cent of the industry's Pounds 29.9bn turnover.
The Chemical Industries Association said the UK chemicals sector was the
first British sector to publish its spending and environmental emissions
figures. It was also the first national chemicals industry to publish such
statistics, the association said.
The association reported that between 1990 and 1992, environmental spending
increased from Pounds 830m to Pounds 1.032bn.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
