<DOCNO>FT934-816</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DLVCCAFTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931222
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Survey of Saudi Arabia (6): One day, the call will be
answered - A special correspondent reports on plans to expand telephone
lines fourfold by 1997
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Over the past five years, the country's demand for telecommunications,
particularly telephone lines, has exceeded all expectations. A Jeddah
newspaper, in an article earlier this month, suggested that 'the average
Saudi' spends more time on the telephone than his counterparts in other Arab
countries.
However, placing an international call at peak business hours in either
Saudi Arabia or the receiving country is much more difficult today than,
say, two years ago. All too often, the caller gets the recorded reply: 'We
are sorry, your call did not go through; please try again later.' Bankers
report long waits for new telephone lines, while many factories are said to
be resorting to portables for which there is less of a wait.
Saudi Telecom, the operational arm of the Posts, Telegraphs &amp; Telephones
ministry, has a target of one telephone, a mobile phone and a pager for one
in every five people. That would mean at least 3m of each item for a
population which last year was officially estimated to be 16.9m, of whom
12.3m were Saudi nationals. The population is said to be increasing by 4 per
cent or nearly 500,000 a year across the country, and possibly by 5 per cent
in the cities. To reach the PTT's target, Saudi Telecom's strategy is to
expand telephone lines nearly fourfold by 1997.
Part of the reason for this surge in demand is that domestic telephone
charges are heavily subsidised. While international calls are more expensive
than in the US or Europe, domestic calls are part of the government's
welfare state benefits to add to a list that includes schooling, medicine,
domestic flights, power, water and some parts of agriculture. Free dialling
within a province was introduced in April 1992 - at the same time as
electricity and water charges were cut for consumers - and the cost of other
telephone calls went down by 40 per cent.
Saudi Telecom is, however, a cash cow. It would make an attractive
proposition for privatisation were it not for the government's concern over
control and monitoring; so that, as has happened more than once in the past
30 years, it has on occasion closed the entire system without warning at
times of acute political sensitivity. Even so, the telecom sector has so
attractive a cash flow that five domestic banks and one offshore bank
recently put together a finance package for the winning bidder of the
outstanding jumbo telephone expansion contract.
Since the 1970s and early 1980s when Sweden's Ericsson with Phillips of the
Netherlands set up the original Dollars 5bn national telecommunications
system, the standard of service has been very high. Overall supervision
under successive three-year management contracts has been with Bell Canada
and more recently with Australian Telecom, whose existing contract will
expire next October. Earlier this month, Saudi and foreign companies were
invited to prepare bids for the next three-year contract.
Until the recent announcement of the jumbo expansion plan, several smaller
works had been commissioned. In 1991 the UK's GPT (General Electric/Plessey
Telecoms), in which Siemens has a 40 per cent interest, was given a Dollars
30m contract to install 2,000 card payphones in the Riyadh, Jeddah, and
Makkah-Madinah areas.
Last year, the US's AT&amp;T surprised the market by offering a 44 per cent
discount on a Dollars 90m gross bid to supply hand-held and vehicle-mounted
mobile telephones; it being standard practice in this market to offer a
discount at the time the bid envelope is opened. At the end of last month, a
Finnish company, Technoman, won a SR28m (Dollars 7.5m) order to set up
200,000 pager lines by 1995, and Siemens last February won a Dollars 120m
contract to supply and install 190,000 telephone lines to help ease the
serious shortage for domestic and business users. But this was only a taster
for the jumbo contract now being evaluated to try to bring supply in line
with demand.
Six pre-qualified companies - AT&amp;T, France's Alcatel, Ericsson with Japan's
NEC, Canada's Northern Telecom and Siemens with input from GPT - have made
offers which with discounts vary from Dollars 3.5bn gross to Dollars 1.6bn
for the PTT's Telephone Expansion Project number 6 (TEP6). This involves
supplying and laying 500,000 to 1.5m lines plus provision for other
infrastructure needs including support buildings, microwave towers,
fibre-optic links, satellite connections, subscriber radio telephones for
rural and desert areas, new switching systems and maintenance. Early this
month, Alcatel was reported to have offered to install 1m lines for the same
price as 500,000. Provision for new cellular telephones, originally part of
the jumbo package, has been taken out, to be bid separately by the same
companies.
Because of the widely differing systems on offer, the technical evaluation
will not be complete until well into next year, by which time the amount of
money available to the PTT ministry will have become partly clearer after
publication of the 1994 budget in January.
When the PTT called for these bids, it also sought supplier financing to be
part of the tender offer. This would involve the export credit agency of the
country or countries concerned, but the kingdom's banks are also so liquid,
and with telecoms having the cash flow that it does, that six banks came up
with their own financing proposal for the winning bidder.
For obvious reasons, the banks are not prepared to discuss details of their
proposal but the logic behind their initiative is not hard to find. Official
budgetary constraints are such that expansion schemes of this kind are more
and more likely to go off-budget; to be financed by bank lending and/or
supplier finance, and possibly equity financing or leasebacks.
To date, the problem has been that even export credit agencies, not to
mention domestic or offshore banks, want a finance ministry guarantee to
ensure that the settlement risk on the total loan money lies with the Saudi
government, even though PTT, as a government ministry, is tantamount to
being a sovereign risk. But the finance ministry is no more likely to give a
guarantee for TEP6 than it was for the recent long-term riyal loan for Saudi
Consolidated Electric Company for the Western Region.
Since equity financing through privatisation would seem not to be an option
in the case of PTT, the banks are having to call on all their innovative
abilities to find ways to take part. One area reportedly being discussed is
for the winning bidder(s) on TEP6 to raise the capital to complete the
contract and to lease the system back to the government.
</TEXT>
