<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Survey of Saudi Arabia (5): Gulf memories run deep - The
foreign policy agenda has changed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The 1990-1991 Gulf crisis has proved a defining episode in the evolution of
Saudi Arabia's foreign policy.
Until Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, senior Saudi officials acknowledge that
their attitude to the region and to the wider world was set primarily by the
experience of others and by the assertion that the Arabs shared a common
heritage. The shock of Iraq's occupation of Kuwait, and, as importantly, the
reaction of other Arab states and organisations to it, taught the kingdom a
lesson which it is still digesting.
The first and most important result is that Saudi Arabia now insists, above
all, that it must have a foreign policy which rests primarily on an
assessment of its own national self-interest.
Senior officials argue that before the invasion of Kuwait, the kingdom was
susceptible to a foreign policy agenda based on the colonial and
post-colonial experiences of other Arab countries. In the three decades from
1960 to 1990 this manifested itself in pan-Arabism, Arab socialism and the
belief that the solution to the region's problems lay essentially in
ever-closer Arab co-operation.
The hollowness of those slogans was brought home to Riyadh by the actions of
President Saddam Hussein. 'If the Arab League had been responsible for
resolving that crisis, then Iraqi troops would still be in Kuwait today,'
comments a Saudi official. Many Saudis remain disgusted by the attitudes
adopted by some fellow members of the Arab League, particularly Jordan,
Yemen and the Palestine Liberation Organisation.
'We cannot forget, and we cannot forgive,' says another official. 'But there
are two things in this life that you cannot escape - families and
neighbours.' Accordingly, Saudi Arabia would not rule out an improvement in
relations with the PLO, Jordan and Yemen, but it would have to be based on
their acceptance of the damage they had done. Equally, there would have to
be a fundamental review of both the organisation and the policies of the
Arab League before the Saudis could feel confident again of its value as a
regional organisation.
'The future effectiveness of the Arab League depends on its ability to
articulate a shared and common purpose,' says a Saudi official. 'It is
weakened and divided. Basic reforms have to be carried out. Above all, this
means that it must give supremacy to international legality.'
The Gulf crisis brought home to Saudi Arabia that there was no other path to
follow. It now emphatically rejects the concept of a separate 'Arab
legality'. The rules of international law have to be applied as much to Arab
nations as they are to the rest of the world.
The concept that there is a different set of rules for Arabs has been
finally buried, along with the former assumption that the main threat to
Middle East stability comes from outside the region. 'It did not come from
the industrialised world, nor did it come from the ideological confrontation
between east and west. It came from within: from the war between Iran and
Iraq and then from Iraq alone,' says an official.
This, in turn, has led Saudi Arabia to review its attitude towards the
provision of aid, or as it was put officially, 'from our policy of acting as
the treasury for other people's expenses'. Nothing is more irksome for
Saudis than the knowledge that its heavy financial commitment to Iraq during
the eight-year conflict with Iran helped President Saddam to acquire the
military muscle to invade Kuwait. It will think long and hard before helping
any neighbouring country to develop its military establishment, but remains
willing to provide assistance 'which could help other countries to build a
better economic and political future'.
It is an indication of how much Saudi attitudes have evolved that 'a better
political future' is also deemed to include greater political pluralism
which, had it been practised in Iraq, might have prevented the invasion of
Kuwait, or at least led to a military pull-out in the face of western
threats.
This does not mean that Saudi Arabia is anywhere near advocating for the
region the democratic processes of the western world, but officials are keen
to stress how much they share the western view of international legality.
Suggestions that the kingdom might have become more dependent on the US in
particular as a result of the Gulf crisis are rejected, but it is now more
openly accepted that a greater commonality of interest has developed between
Washington and Riyadh.
It applies, with qualifications, to the US 'dual containment' policy towards
Iraq and Iran. Insofar as that policy articulates the need for both Baghdad
and Tehran to abide by international resolutions, it enjoys Saudi support,
but there would be less enthusiasm in Riyadh for any attempt to isolate the
two countries.
However, the depth of suspicion in Saudi Arabia about Iran's intentions
continues, despite cosmetic signs of an improvement in diplomatic relations.
Saudi Arabia suspects that the Shah of Iran, Ayatollah Khomeini and
President Rafsanjani all shared a common desire to be the dominant political
and economic force in the Gulf, a view reinforced by Iran's recent
unilateral actions in asserting sovereignty over Abu Musa, and the Greater
and Lesser Tumbs islands, near the Strait of Hormuz.
Saudi Arabia has also welcomed officially the declaration of principles
signed by Israel and the PLO in Washington on September 13, but wants to see
far more progress towards a comprehensive Middle East peace settlement
before it is willing to speculate about any wider implications.
In particular, officials are totally dismissive of suggestions by Israel
that Saudi Arabia could be one of the next Arab countries to establish
formal diplomatic relations. 'They are just dreaming', says a senior
official. He is also sceptical about the possibility on an early end to the
primary Arab boycott of Israel, while pointing out that Saudi Arabia has
already taken steps to phase out the application of the secondary boycott,
which discriminates against international companies which do business with
Israel.
Riyadh is also being cautious over the extent of its financial commitment to
the Palestinian interim self-governing authority which will take over
administrative functions in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip in the
wake of the Israeli withdrawal or redeployment of its forces.
The Saudi Fund for Devel- opment will channel the kingdom's initial
first-year pledge of Dollars 100m, designed to improve basic infrastructure
such as roads, schools and housing.
The fund has also agreed to provide further funds during the five-year
transitional phase, but will wait to see the progress that is made in
disbursing the initial tranche before announcing the size of further
financial support.
Officials emphasise that there is no question of the funds being directed to
Tunis, the present headquarters of the PLO, another reminder of how deep the
Gulf war memories run.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SAZ  Saudi Arabia, Middle East.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
    P9199 General Government, NEC.
    P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT934-820</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DLVCCAFPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931222
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Survey of Environmental Management (4): Quality concern - A
green tinge to a company's financial statement may not add up to much
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Environmental reporting may be on the rise, but much more needs to be done
to justify the quantity of trees that are being cut down to sustain it.
A substantial and growing number of companies now have at least a green tint
to the pages of their financial statements. The concern is over the quality
of the information that they provide: much is more hollow words than
meaningful content.
A survey released last month by KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountancy firm,
canvassed the practices of 690 of the leading companies in Belgium, Canada,
Denmark, France, Germany, Ireland, the Netherlands, Portugal, the UK and the
US*.
More than 100 companies produced a separate environmental report, while 400
at least referred to green issues somewhere in their annual report. As
Professor Rob Gray, director of the Centre for Social and Environmental
Accounting Research at the University of Dundee, puts it, this represents a
'phenomenal' upsurge in the last few years.
But when it comes to issues such as consistency, comparability,
accountability or the degree to which information is verifiable, the results
are more disappointing - and in line with other similar findings.
Just 83 of the companies in the KPMG study set quantitative targets. Even
though 128 provide some figures to illustrate their performance, the
majority were just brief references to issues such as costs of environmental
investment.
A few also mentioned the fines imposed on them, although there was a general
tendency to highlight 'good news' and ignore the bad, particularly among US
companies. KPMG argues this reflects concerns over the risk of exposing
themselves to litigation.
When it came to any indication that the information provided was backed up
by any guarantees, the results were also disappointing. Only 63 companies
disclosed that they had had an internal environmental audit, and 33 an
external audit.
Mr Kim Hayworth, partner in charge of KPMG's National Environment Unit in
London, admits that the growth in green reporting has been slower than many
expected.
'The pressure to report is not strong,' he says. 'It is an issue but it is
not at the top of the agenda yet.
'Also, companies are still trying to put together the information on
environmental performance. It does not emerge easily.'
Mr Hayworth argues that this is partly linked to the growing
decentralisation of the management of organisations. 'It is difficult to
demand subsidiaries to provide data.'
On the other hand, he stresses that a number of voluntary corporate
reporting initiatives are being developed. 'For a company starting up now,
the standard is very high,' he says. Reports are expected to be logical,
honest and full of quantifiable data.
He cites as examples the most recent reports of companies such as British
Telecom, RTZ and Thorn, which are beginning to provide considerable
information on responsibilities and quantified targets for environmental
improvement.
A handful go further still, such as BSO/Origin, the Dutch computer services
company, which has attempted to put a cost on all of its activities
affecting the environment.
Aside from the specific examples, Mr Hayworth also draws some consolation
from several new voluntary environmental reporting guidelines which are
being developed, such as the Public Environmental Reporting Initiative in
the US, and the work of the Global Environmental Management Initiative.
The question is how far these guidelines are relevant to smaller companies,
or to those outside the industry sectors which have developed them: normally
in the highly-regulated chemical or extractive areas.
More generally, there are few attempts by governments to impose stricter
reporting. One exception is the Netherlands, where a draft law proposes a
requirement on companies to publish detailed information on environmental
impact and improvement plans.
In the absence of tougher legal requirements, there is one other factor
which may drive companies to implement strict environmental management
standards internally although these may not be reported: commercial
pressure.
That will come primarily from litigation, but also partly from companies
which are beginning to demand accreditation or other evidence of sound
environmental management from their suppliers.
Elsewhere, and in less litigious sectors, voluntary initiatives are the
norm.
Both BS 7750, the British standard on environmental management, and the
European Union's Ecological Management and Auditing Scheme (Emas) have been
unveiled. But both are awaiting final tweaking and any significant take-up.
Emas was substantially diluted over the last few years as a result of
intensive lobbying from industry, switching it from a mandatory into a
voluntary scheme, and from something with company-wide scope to being
site-specific.
Despite the changes, there are still considerable issues to be resolved in
its implementation. A pilot study on Emas completed over the summer by PA
Consulting, showed considerable enthusiasm for the concept.
But there were concerns about whether the considerable additional costs  -
particularly related to external verification of reports - would outweigh
the benefits, especially when applied to smaller companies.
Mr Tony Bishop, manager for environment services at the firm, argues for
several distinct types of environmental management system across different
industry sectors rather than a uniform approach, depending on the degree of
formality required and the environmental impact.
Meanwhile, if companies still need considerable prompting to develop
meaningful statements, the consulting industry that has grown up around the
environment equally needs to improve its performance. There is wide variety
in the quality of services provided.
The Institute of Environmental Assessment has launched an environmental
auditors' registration association scheme for individuals. The Association
of Environmental Consultancies has launched a registration scheme for member
firms.
How independent and effective they will prove remains to be seen. But
without high standards, the surfeit of consultants peddling management
systems and environmental reporting advice to their clients could simply add
to confusion and waste.
</TEXT>
<XX>
