<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Survey of Environmental Management (5): Not a lot of cover
to run for - Insurance is causing persistent management headaches
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pollution is giving Mr Alan Fleming, the executive director of the the UK's
Association of Risk and Insurance Managers, a headache.
Mr Fleming views the shortage of cover for environmental liabilities as one
of the biggest problems facing the 300 or so industrial and commercial
insurance buyers represented by the association.
Faced by legal uncertainties and fears that they could be landed with the
costs of cleaning up more than 500,000 acres of polluted land, insurers are
increasing their prices and reining back the scope of protection offered to
customers. 'There is no question that it is an important issue,' says Mr
Fleming. 'The big concern is retrospective liabilities. Unless the
legislation becomes absolutely clear, I am afraid we will find another area
where the insurance industry is not responding,' he adds.
Insurers are concerned by several trends.
The establishment of a more rigorous regime of pollution control and
remediation in the UK. The 1990 Environmental Protection Act provides powers
for local authorities to force site occupiers to clean up contamination
irrespective of proof of fault.
Similarly, the 1991 Water Resources Act makes provision for cleaning up
polluted rivers. Under the legislation, bankers foreclosing on a loan to a
property company could become liable for the cost of cleaning up
contamination.
Europe: Insurers are also worried about potential developments in European
law, following indications that some EU officials favour an extension of
strict liability in relation to clean-up costs.
Recent common law cases: The ruling of an appeal court last year, in a case
involving Eastern Counties Leather and Cambridge Water, caused particular
consternation before it was overturned by the House of Lords on December 9.
The appeal court awarded well in excess of Pounds 1m in damages and costs
against Eastern Counties Leather even though it found that the company had
not been negligent when it regularly spilled chemical into ground water.
Although the pollution was 'unforeseen', the court found Eastern Counties
liable in 'nuisance' - an older legal concept in which it is not necessary
to show fault.
Another recent case involving allegations of land contamination by Coalite,
a chemicals company, has also caused some controversy.
Coalite was allegedly responsible for polluting land and a river near three
farms at Bolsover in Derbyshire, thereby restricting the farmers from
selling dioxin-contaminated produce for more than a year. The company
eventually agreed to pay 'substantial damages' (thought to be at least
Pounds 200,000) to the farmers in an out of court settlement. Coalite is
still negotiating with Royal Insurance, its insurers.
Reinsurance: Finally, companies are also under some pressure from their own
reinsurers to reduce the coverage they give for pollution. It is understood
that a decision taken by French insurers, to exclude pollution cover from
their liability policies sold from the beginning of 1994, followed decisions
by large European reinsurance companies.
UK insurers withdrew cover for 'gradual' pollution - typically caused by
leakages or seepage of contaminants such as in the Cambridge Water case - in
April 1990. Even so, many observers believe they could be vulnerable to
claims for 'historic' pollution against policies underwritten before then
(in the same way as US insurers have received claims on comprehensive
general liability policies before pollution exclusions were introduced in
the 1970s).
Like their US counterparts, UK insurers underwrote liability policies on a
so-called 'occurrence' basis, in which the relevant policy for a claim is
the one which covers the year when the 'insurable' event occurred, rather
than the year in which the claim was made (the so-called 'claims made'
basis).
In a number of cases US courts have ruled that site owners and operators who
were ordered to clean up can claim on insurance policies stretching back to
the original point at which pollution is deemed to have begun.
Some observers believe that British insurers could ultimately be exposed to
a heavy clean up bill. Mr Randolph Fields, a lawyer who has developed a
thriving business in researching insurance coverages in the US, is confident
that he can locate the historic coverages in the UK and warns that the UK
industry faces liabilities of 'catastrophic proportions'.
Mr Tony Baker, head of public affairs at the association, plays down the
danger, suggesting that, at most, UK insurers will face a maximum of a tenth
of an estimated clean up bill of Pounds 30bn. He points out that much of the
UK's worst pollution has been caused by nationalised industries - such as
coal and gas - which have no insurance cover. He suggests that, even then,
in the worse possible circumstances the resulting bill of Pounds 3bn would
be paid over decades, diluting its impact.
Even so, Mr Baker concedes that insurers are considering the introduction of
further restrictions to public liability policies and could withdraw
coverage even for 'sudden and accidental' pollution, which occurs, for
example, when chemicals are spilled.
'People could withdraw cover from public liability policies, making
protection available on a 'stand alone' basis which would have to be
separately underwritten,' he says.
Already buyers have suffered sharp increases in prices over the last 18
months. Companies whose operations are deemed to be high risk' - such as
waste management companies - can now pay as much as 1 per cent of the annual
turnover for insurance.
One composite insurer has already made even limited pollution cover
dependent on proof that the buyer of the policy has taken measures to
control environmental risks, and brokers fear that the market could
introduce new risk management criteria - for example, adhesion to new
British environmental standards.
Already a number of companies including Swiss Re, AIG Europe, ECS
Underwriting and Zurich offer a policy covering against the risk of gradual
pollution, which is linked to measures such as site surveys, environmental
audits and the remediation of pre-existing contamination. The policies are
expensive and so far take-up has been limited.
Brokers believe that the scope of these new types of policy could become
broader, wider, and their take-up common, as the availability of traditional
insurance cover is reduced.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
