<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Survey of Saudi Arabia (4): Royal boundary to free speech -
The stirrings of political life in the kingdom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When a middle-ranking member of the House of Saud opens a conversation by
suggesting that most of the Council of Ministers should be dismissed for
having failed to come up with any new ideas for managing the nation's
economy, it is clear that political life in the kingdom is rather less
moribund than its detractors suggest. Saudi Arabia is not facing an economic
crisis, he insists, but is suffering from over-centralised, incompetent
ministries best noted for the opportunities they have missed.
Such comments to visitors are still likely to be made only by those
confident of their royal status, but they do reflect a widely held view
among the younger and more entrepreneurial generation of Saudis that a
fundamental revision of government policies is required. The suggestion that
too many ministers have been too long at their posts for the good of the
country is not a particularly new phenomenon, but it has gained wider
acceptance as a result of the Gulf war and the consequent impact on the
kingdom's exchequer.
King Fahd may have responded to those concerns in August when he finally
named the 60 members of a consultative council (majlis al-shura). The
concept of such a council was first raised three decades ago, and given the
monarchy's legendary caution in initiating reforms, it is likely to be some
time before the role and importance of the council can be fairly assessed.
Reactions to the limited powers vested in the council, and the composition
of its members, have varied widely. Taken at face value, the consultative
aspect of the council's role appears paramount. It cannot initiate
discussions and will deal only with issues referred to it. Its
recommendations need not be adopted and will be carried forward only if they
coincide with those of the Council of Ministers.
Mr Mohammed Ibrahim al-Jubair, the speaker of the council and a former
minister of justice, will have considerable authority over the working of
the council. Deliberations are to be kept secret, members cannot speak at
full council sessions for more than 10 minutes without special dispensation,
and no documents can be removed from the council building. For critics of
the council, particularly those yearning for a more westernised, democratic
reform of Saudi political life, the king's proposals smack more of a rubber
stamp than of genuine reform.
However, within the kingdom, that seems to be very much a minority view.
Many Saudis appear genuinely impressed by the quality and educational
attainments of the council members and are cautiously optimistic that their
deliberations will add an important new layer of ideas and debate within the
decision-making process. King Fahd, who is also prime minister, can choose
to adopt the council's recommendations just as much as he may reject them.
To that extent, the council could well become the main vehicle through which
policy options are aired and trial balloons floated without any endorsement
or commitment by the ruling family.
Several western diplomats admit that they were surprised by the council's
composition. They had presumed that the members would strongly reflect the
tribal, regional and religious characteristics of Saudi society. Instead,
the professions are powerfully represented with 32 of the 60 members having
gained advanced degrees at western universities, two-thirds of them in the
US. The conservative religious establishment is only modestly represented
and no members of the royal family are included.
Conversations with the new members of the council reveal how seriously they
are approaching their task. The appointments are full-time, salaried and for
an initial period of four years. By the middle of last month most of them
had already gathered in Riyadh and initial work had begun on the formation
of committees where the bulk of the council's work is expected to be done.
Members acknowledge that they are entering uncharted territory and are
unsure what their influence may be. However, several have indicated that
they expect to be given substantial topics to research and debate, such as
methods for improving government revenues, how to achieve an overall
reduction in the budget deficit, together with defence, foreign and social
issues.
Some senior members of the business community hope that the council will
evolve into a primary source for new legislation, allowing the council of
ministers to concentrate more on its role as the executive arm of
government. 'Ministers just do not have the time to think about
legislation,' says one businessman. 'They should be left to continue their
primary role which is executive, and rely on the majlis al-shura for the new
ideas.'
King Fahd has also taken modest steps to reform the council of ministers. A
decree issued in August sets a four-year term for ministers but this can be
extended, both for the council as a whole and for individual ministers. It
also specifies that ministers should not hold other government jobs,
although exceptions are provided for. Similarly, restrictions are placed on
ministers following separate business careers.
These actions, together with the creation of a second ministry devoted to
Islamic affairs, could also be interpreted as a response to criticism by
radical Moslems. But the latest group to seek public attention for its
grievances, the so-called Committee for the Defence of Legitimate Rights,
set up last year, has also been left in no doubt that the government will
not tolerate overt criticism. Some members of the 60-strong group, drawn
mostly from a conservative, academic background, have been detained, and
others banned from leaving the kingdom.
Such strong official reaction might appear to dampen any western hope that
the ruling family is moving towards a marginally greater degree of popular
participation in government. But for Saudis it is more likely to have
reinforced the understanding that criticism of the king and his government
should not stray outside the family domain. In theory, a commoner can say
whatever he wishes to King Fahd, and will be listened to. But if he
challenges that convention, then displeasure is likely to be demonstrated.
It is a lesson which the consultative council will, initially at least,
observe with care.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SAZ  Saudi Arabia, Middle East.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
    P9111 Executive Offices.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
