<PROFILE>_AN-DLVCCAFLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931222
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Survey of Saudi Arabia (2): Budget targets may not be met -
Impact of the Gulf war on the economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Saudi Arabia is well versed in handling the peaks and troughs of oil export
earnings. The 1980s saw annual variations of up to Dollars 100bn as the
kingdom was affected by sudden changes in supply and demand, and fully used
its role as the swing producer within the Organisation of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to smooth out fluctuations for the greater long-term
benefit of the producer nations.
However, the financial impact of the Gulf war, particularly on the level of
Saudi Arabia's reserves, has put an end to that role. The kingdom is now
like any other member of Opec in that it will need to maximise its oil
export revenues for the foreseeable future if it is to prevent its budget
and current account deficits from running out of control.
The government can fairly point to the fact that it has already enjoyed a
measure of success with deficit-reduction policies during the five-year
period before Iraq invaded Kuwait in August 1990 and threw its programme
badly off course. During the second half of the 1980s, Saudi Arabia cut its
overall budget deficit by more than half, from over 20 per cent of gross
national product to less than 10 per cent. During the same period the
current account deficit on the balance of payments was reduced by 5 per cent
of GDP to 11 per cent.
But President Saddam Hussein put an end to those creditable achievements.
The average budget deficit for the years 1990 and 1991 came to about 17 per
cent of GDP and the current account deficit climbed back to about 14 per
cent.
It has been the government's stated intention to get back on track as
swiftly as possible. Its 1992 budget was supposed to see a sharp drop in
spending with total expenditure set at just over Dollars 44bn, compared with
an annualised rate of Dollars 61bn over the two previous war-affected years.
This should have seen the deficit decline to a forecast 3.3 per cent of GNP.
In the event, the government failed to reduce spending by its target of 28
per cent and provisional figures suggest that at about Dollars 55bn, it was
some Dollars 11bn over budget. As a percentage of GNP, the deficit was
nearly three times larger than the target.
Although officials decline to discuss budget details, it seems clear that
capital expenditure was substantially larger than forecast and there was
also slippage in the announced programme of reducing subsidies, particularly
those related to the agricultural sector. The government has promised to try
harder in the current financial year and there is evidence that it is having
greater success, particularly in reducing the subsidies paid to wheat
producers. The main cuts were designed to fall on project expenditure,
especially that related to security.
However, there is little additional evidence, real or anecdotal, to indicate
that firm government action has been taken. The spending target of Dollars
48.5bn appears unrealistic and the final figure could well turn out to be
within the Dollars 53-55bn range. At the same time, government revenues
appear certain to fall below the forecast Dollars 45bn as a result of
weakening oil prices. This would suggest another budget deficit this year of
more than Dollars 10bn. With little or no growth forecast in the overall
economy, the aimed-for reduction in the budget deficit as a percentage of
GDP will not be achieved.
This failure has to be seen in the context of the concerns expressed
privately six months ago by a visiting team from the International Monetary
Fund. The mission warned then that even if the Saudi government met its 1993
budget targets, total debt would rise from 56 per cent of GDP to some 60 per
cent. Unless further stringent measures were taken in the succeeding years
the debt-to-GDP ratio would rise to 80 per cent by 1997.
These forecasts were also made on the assumption of a modest annual increase
in the level of oil revenues. But, the Fund added, if the government failed
to meet its 1993 targets, which now seems certain, the medium-term deficits
would be even larger and debt servicing would place an increasingly heavy
burden on budgetary resources.
Although the authorities remain confident that the banking sector's high
liquidity level will continue to finance the budget deficit through the
traditional means of government development bonds, there are fears among the
private sector that in the medium term its access to funds could be
squeezed. Such a prospect should be an additional cause of alarm for a
government which for nearly a decade has insisted that the private sector
must take a growing responsibility for providing economic growth.
One probably inevitable consequence of all these pressures is that the
government will have to turn to taxation, in some form, as a way of boosting
its revenues. Ministers have been adamant during the past two years that
social conditions have not permitted either a significant cut in subsidies
or any form of additional charges. On the contrary, subsidies on some
utilities were actually increased in order to offset the modest increase in
inflation stemming from the Gulf war. But the nettle will eventually have to
be grasped, and there are some indications that the government is already
looking at modest initiatives, such as a tax on international and domestic
airline tickets.
There is also considerable scope on the expenditure side, where military and
infrastructure projects appear to be ripe targets for cuts or delays. The
Gulf war experience demonstrated that the kingdom's ability to resist
external threats resulted as much on the facilities it was able to provide
for foreign armies as it did on Saudi Arabia's own armed forces. Those
facilities proved their value, and military experts argue that the kingdom
requires more time to absorb the equipment it now has, rather than embarking
on a programme of new acquisitions. In other words, it could well do without
do without some of the Dollars 30bn of weaponry it has contracted to buy
since the invasion of Kuwait.
Such cuts or delays would also help to ease the balance of payments problems
which have mirrored those of the budget. The current account deficit last
year at Dollars 19.4bn was substantially above forecast and casts serious
doubt on the outcome for 1993 which, it had been hoped, would not rise much
above Dollars 11bn, or around 9.3 per cent of GDP. Even on that basis, the
IMF had projected a worsening current account deficit over the next four
years, reaching some Dollars 19bn in 1997, assuming also strong capital
inflows. Weakening oil prices and a lower than expected level of foreign
investment in Saudi Arabia would obviously make the picture considerably
gloomier.
The problem is exacerbated by the loss of the reserve cushion caused by the
Gulf war. Net official foreign assets were estimated at Dollars 72bn at the
end of last year, equivalent to about 29 months of imports. But this tells
only part of the story. Over 30 per cent of the assets managed by the Saudi
Arabian Monetary Agency is held as statutory cover for the currency. Another
30 per cent is held against letters of credit and liabilities to the
commercial banks, while some Dollars 20bn or more represents loans to Iraq
and other countries which are most unlikely ever to be repaid.
In the middle of this year, liquid funds actually available to Sama were put
at a little over Dollars 7bn, and were unlikely to show much, if any,
improvement in the short to medium term.
Further external borrowing is, of course, an option, but there is no
evidence that Saudi Arabia has tapped international markets beyond the
Dollars 4.5bn it raised at the time of the Gulf war. Some bankers suggested
recently that the fact the government has not borrowed this year indicates
that the authorities are proving more successful than had been supposed in
controlling the current account deficit. This may also have served to dampen
recurrent speculative pressures against the riyal.
Some Saudis continue to argue privately for a modest devaluation against the
dollar, but there is no evidence that the government sees any benefit to the
economy from such action. On the contrary, it almost certainly fears the
damage that a devaluation would have on local confidence and the consequent
impact on capital inflows from abroad.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
