<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Survey of Environmental Management (3): Ambitious and
sprawling - UK Regulations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the reliable moments of comedy during environmental conferences is
the announcement from the 'chair' that there will be a workshop on 'green
industry'. Delegates will promptly begin to move towards the corners of the
seminar room allocated to alternative topics: animals, world trade, perhaps
global warming.
That will leave a small group of chemical industry executives and the newer
breed of environmental campaigners eyeing each other nervously before they
settle down to talk about whether regulation is really making business
greener.
Industry is one of the oldest targets of environmental pressure groups. The
lobbyists might credit themselves with some success: regulation to curb
industrial pollution is now at the heart of the UK's environmental policy.
Yet the government is still besieged with complaints from both
environmentalists and industrialists that the rules are not working: too
loose, says the 'green' side; too bureaucratic, says the 'brown'. Is either
chorus right?
The core of the regulation is set out in the 1990 Environmental Protection
Act, an ambitious and sprawling piece of 'enabling' legislation created by
Mr Chris Patten, then environment secretary, when popular green enthusiasm
was at its height.
The principle underpinning the rules is the cumbersomely named 'Batneec' or
'best available technique not entailing excessive cost'. The task of
applying it falls to the pollution inspectorate.
Its director, Mr David Slater, has a modern taste for 'long-term dialogue
with companies', and for 'cost-benefit' analysis. He argues that 'We're not
in the business of putting business out of business'. Instead, he and his
inspectors like to spend time discussing with individual companies how they
can minimise waste.
Industry, at first hostile to much of the new regulation, has recently been
making more conciliatory sounds, and companies say they appreciate the
flexibility the inspectorate is showing. In the early days of the Act, as
all parties were struggling to interpret Batneec, there were many fierce
complaints, particularly from the chemical industry, that the rules were
unworkable.
Mr John Cox, director of the Chemical Industries Association, which
represents some 250 UK companies, says 'there are still problems of
interpreting Batneec, but it is much better than it was'. In the early
months, he says, local inspectors often displayed 'a different understanding
of the regulations from the central inspectorate'. But some sticking points
have now been ironed out, he says.
While environmentalists are increasingly willing to contemplate cooperation
with industry rather than confrontation, many have regarded the
inspectorate's measures - and industry's mellowing response - with
suspicion. They particularly dislike some of the inspectorate's recent
decisions - such as allowing two power stations to burn orimulsion as fuel,
which campaigners have dubbed 'the world's filthiest fuel'.
In particular, they accuse him of having 'gone soft' on polluting industries
during the recession. While there are indications in parts of government
policy that environmental aims have been sacrificed because of the fragility
of economic recovery - environment department officials say privately that
they regard the construction industry as out of bounds at present - the
inspectorate denies that it has come under such pressure.
Some of that suspicion may seem inevitable, given the history of mistrust
between the environmental movement and industry. But criticism of the
regulation and the inspectorate is justified, some economists say.
Mr Dieter Helm, director of Oxera, the forecasting group, says 'the
structure that we have now facilitates 'regulatory capture' (an
over-sympathetic attitude towards companies by their regulator) because the
inspectorate has so much discretion with applying the rules, and so much of
the judgment depends on examining individual sites'.
A second weakness, he argues, is that the rules are 'technology driven, and
not subjected to a proper scrutiny of costs'. In his view, the 'Bat' element
of the 'Batneec' rule has been applied more than the 'neec', which entails
more difficult analysis.
For example, he argues, under present rules, coal burning power stations are
urged to fit flue gas desulphurisation (FGD) to cut sulphur emissions, which
have been linked to acid rain. It is true that FGD is the best available
technique for power stations, he says, but if cost is taken into account, it
would be cheaper to build gas-fired stations.
Failure to consider costs thoroughly has been a flaw of much environmental
regulation, and industrialists and economists - and some 'green' campaigners
 -are agreed that closer attention is merited. That will not address,
however, the concern of environmentalists and other outside observers that
the regulator is too 'soft', if not 'captured' by industry.
Because of those concerns, Mr Slater is likely to find that he continues to
be the subject of suspicion and intense scrutiny by the environmental
movement. He will have a tough job as he continues to iron out the lumps in
Britain's well meaning but sometimes ill thought out pollution legislation.
As Mr Helm puts it, 'if you started from scratch, you wouldn't design
regulation like this'.
