<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Survey of Environmental Management (1): Eyes open wider to
the green scene - Running a business with an eye to its impact on the
environment may not improve profits - but there are other motives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The high tide of popular green enthusiasm has partly ebbed away, but its
legacy across Europe and North America is layers of environmental regulation
directed at industry and commerce. It has left, too, cohorts of consultants
urging companies to improve their environmental management.
That exhortation covers a wide range of issues. Broadly, environmental
management means managing a business with an eye to its impact on the
environment and to environmental regulation. Surveys have shown that
companies are increasingly paying attention to these issues.
Last month's study of more than 200 environmental managers by Environmental
Data Services, the well-respected journal, found that two thirds had been
appointed in the last three years, and one third in the last year. KPMG Peat
Marwick, the consultants, found that more than 40 per cent of 700 companies
it questioned recently in industrialised countries published statements of
environmental policy.
The question of how management should take account of environmental concerns
also contains a trickier conundrum: whether cleaning up the environment can
be commercially worthwhile. There is fierce debate between those who see the
environment and the new regulation as an extra layer of cost on business,
and those who argue that 'greener' can mean richer.
The costs of cleaning up, certainly, have become increasingly clear. As
governments have enforced the new rules, some industrial and commercial
costs have risen - in many cases passed on to the consumer. That recognition
is behind the UK government's decision to tangle with Brussels over the
question of whether some water quality standards are unnecessarily high. The
message behind the higher fuel and road taxes in the UK's Budget last month
 -measures presented as 'green' - was also that a clean environment costs
money.
But at the same time ministers and many consultants argue that the
environment and the new regulation offer businesses new opportunities which
only the most stubborn would ignore. The traditional confrontation between
industry and environmentalists is giving way to co-operation.
There is no simple adjudication of that debate. Few figures are available to
show how much environmental protection is costing industry. Nor are there
many answers that apply beyond specific, local cases.
Of the reasons commonly given why it is worthwhile for businesses to improve
environmental management, a few are plausible; many are unconvincing.
Reducing the risk of prosecution under environmental regulations is one of
the best reasons for improving environmental management. Environmental
lawyers believe that companies' fear about potential liabilities is the
reason why they are so busy. Under the 1990 Environmental Protection Act,
directors and managers can also be held personally liable for the company's
pollution and can be subject to criminal prosecution.
Increasingly, bankers and insurers survey their exposure to customers'
environmental obligations, and want customers to demonstrate that adequate
controls are in place.
Improving public image is a powerful motive, although the benefits are hard
to quantify. Mr John Cox, director of the Chemical Industries Association,
which represents some 250 UK companies, says: 'The fall in the chemical
industry's reputation coincides with growing public concern about pollution.
It creates a political climate where legislators feel more bound to
legislate, and it certainly can affect planning permission'.
For example, he argues, industry needs a nationwide network of incinerators,
but because of public opposition to incinerators, it is difficult for waste
companies to get permission even to expand existing plants. 'We have never
been able to quantify what the poor image is costing us but we do say it is
a real cost to the bottom line and represents a threat to our freedom to
invest as we require'.
Minimising waste and saving resources, a favourite mantra of consultants,
raises the question of why businesses were not making the savings already.
The answer is that they should have been doing so, but the extra discipline
of regularly looking at their impact on the environment helps companies
locate new savings, according to Mr Martin Houldin, head of the environment
unit at KPMG Peat Marwick. 'In recession there is a drive to get costs down,
but they then creep up again as management priorities change'.
He argues that tightening regulation on waste disposal means that the
factory is 'no longer seen as a black box from which waste just comes out -
managers are looking more at the internal use of resources'. For example, as
regulators and water companies have increased the cost of drawing water and
discharging effluent to rivers, even small companies are finding it
worthwhile to recover, treat and re-use water themselves.
Finding new markets. Environment ministers are fond of arguing that sales of
environmental technology provide a new business opportunity. The success of
UK water companies, notably North West Water, in winning overseas contacts
for improving water quality, is a case in point. But these opportunities are
accessible only to a small pool of companies compared to the number affected
by tightening environmental regulation.
Improving competitive advantage. One of the most difficult claims to assess
is whether alertness to environmental issues gives companies an advantage in
selling their products. In some, the answer is yes: for example, motor
manufacturers expecting fuel prices or taxes to rise will find it worthwhile
to develop more fuel-efficient cars.
Companies which accurately anticipate these trends may then find they can
secure a competitive advantage within the arena where the taxes or rules
apply. It is also in their interest for the rules to be vigorously enforced.
However they could find themselves handicapped by a higher cost structure
compared to countries with looser environmental regulation - a concern which
the European chemical industry has voiced strongly.
It is also difficult to judge whether consumers prefer 'green' products and
will pay more for them. Claims that consumers would tolerate a 'green
premium' have been called into question by recession - price has become a
greater determinant of preferences, some surveys report.
Consultants acknowledge the difficulties of estimating the benefits of
environmental management. Mr Houldin says: 'There are very few companies who
will say that there is already a net financial benefit in what they have
done. But they would not be taking these steps if they did not believe there
would be a benefit.'
Complex environmental regulation means there is a need for companies to keep
abreast of environmental regulation and changes in customers' tastes. But
governments are worried about the costs of cleaning up the environment,
concerned that these costs should be compared with the environmental
benefits before regulation is passed.
The fashionable claim that environmental management is a wand to transform
the expensive process of complying with regulation environment into a
business opportunity has not been proven, and it ignores the unavoidable
costs of making the environment cleaner.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
