<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / London Stock Exchange: Caution on plan for Gas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The market registered its displeasure over the government's moves to remove
British Gas's monopoly in the domestic gas market and to impose a split of
the company's trading and transportation divisions.
British Gas shares, which reached an all-time high of 360p only last week,
came under increasingly intense pressure yesterday, sliding to a day's low
of 346p before stabilising and closing a net 10 off at 347p. Turnover of 10m
shares was well above the stock's usual levels of activity.
Energy specialists said the real disappointment for the market came with
news that competition in the domestic gas market will hit British Gas much
sooner than the industry and the City had expected. 'Competition is coming
early; British Gas now faces a progressive attack on the most profitable
segments of its business; the shares remain a sell,' said the oil and gas
team at Nomura.
The curtain came down on the interim results season from the utilities
sectors with a top of the range interim payment from Wessex Water. But not
even a 9.6 per cent increase in the dividend could prevent Wessex shares
mirroring a broad retreat by the utilities following publication of the
government's proposals for British Gas.
Wessex shares opened higher at 722p, buoyed by the dividend news, but
quickly fell away to end the session a net 3 down at 714p. Increases in
dividends announced by the water companies in recent weeks have averaged
around 8 per cent.
Market worries about increased regulatory vigilance now focus on the water
regulator's periodic review time-table, which next summer will see Ofwat
announce the companies' individual 'K factors', their regulatory pricing
formulae.
The FT-SE 100 constituents showed falls of 14 common to Anglian Water, 592p,
and Severn Trent, 604p, while Thames dropped 16 to 580p and North West 11 to
581p.
The power generators, however, held up well as the market continued to adopt
the view that a reference to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission is still
avoidable if PowerGen and National Power can reach agreement on prices and
power station sales to help increase competition.
National Power settled a shade higher at 475p and PowerGen eased 4 to 535p.
The regional electricity companies performed badly, similarly affected by
fears that Offer, the electricity regulator, will harden its attitude on K
factors. Southern, the only rec in the FT-SE 100, lost 7 at 700p.
A negative note from NatWest Securities triggered renewed weakness in
Enterprise Oil, which retreated 12 to 454p. NatWest cast doubts on the
security of Enterprise's dividend 'if oil prices stabilise below Dollars 16
a barrel', and said Enterprise is currently trading at 'a huge 52 per cent
premium to our asset value of 305p based on Dollars 16 real oil prices; and
even at a 19 per cent premium to our Dollars 18 asset value of 391p'.
Conglomerate Hanson eased 3 to 273 1/2 p after reports that it was
considering a possible bid of up to Dollars 3bn for all, or part of, Borden,
the US food and chemicals group.
Internationally traded pharmaceutical issues were weak again in response to
a lacklustre New York market. Glaxo slipped 4 to 703p and Zeneca 6 to 795p.
The bid talk that had previously given some relief to troubled Fisons was
not in evidence and the shares receded 3 to 112p.
The first of what is expected to be a rush of property groups seeking market
listings was provided by Chelsfield. The shares made their debut at 155p and
finished at 180p.
Several other private companies are in the process of preparing for
flotation, taking advantage of investor appetite for the sector and raising
valuable investment funds in the process. The potential market value of the
companies is in excess of Pounds 1bn.
A tumble by the Hong Kong market, plus news that an inquiry into the Bombay
stock market scandal had called for severe punishments to be imposed on the
four international banks involved, put Standard Chartered shares under
pressure. They dropped to 1062p early in the session, before rallying to end
15 off at 1179p. Turnover reached an above average 1.5m shares.
Bank of Scotland was active and lost 6 at 225p, with James Capel thought to
have adopted a more cautious stance on the stock.
Profit-taking lowered TSB 4 to 253p, with turnover expanding to 3.2m shares.
However, there was always good underlying support for the shares, according
to dealers, with persistent bid stories underscored by expectations of a
good set of preliminary figures when the bank reports in mid-January.
A Kleinwort Benson buy recommendation was responsible for driving
housebuilder Wilson Connolly 14 ahead to a year's best of 213p - within 10
of the stock's all-time high reached in July 1987.
The beleaguered food retail sector's recent good run came to an end on
rumours that a renewed price initiative was being kept under wraps for the
new year by one of the leading supermarket groups.
Tesco was the worst hit, retreating 9 to 211p. J. Sainsbury slid 13 1/2 to
435p, while Argyll Group fell 8 to 280p.
Among food manufacturers, an upbeat trading message by the chairman of
Berisford International helped the shares climb 5 to 111p. Elsewhere, the
sector steadied in the face of a weak market. Both Unilever and United
Biscuits trod water, while Northern Foods was squeezed up 6 to 217p and
Cadbury-Schweppes added 7 at 513p. NatWest Securities was said to be
pointing out the merits of Hillsdown Holdings, ahead 3 at 160p.
Profit-takers were out in force in the drinks sector. Grand Metropolitan was
one of the few to escape, the shares catching up from their recent subdued
run and rallying 6 1/2 to 466p. Greenalls' good form continued, adding 5 at
455p.
British Aerospace gained 5 at 406p, with dealers citing the recent
recommendation from SG Warburg. Rolls-Royce shed 3 1/2 to 163p as one
broker, believed to be NatWest Securities, was telling clients to sell the
stock down to 155p.
Powerscreen International, which recently rebuffed allegations of a tax
probe that had undermined the shares, continued its recovery, putting on 5
at 308p. Simon Engineering rose 5 to 121p following comment on the recent
sale of TR Oil Services. Weir Group firmed 8 to 291p, with Credit Lyonnais
Laing said to be recommending the stock.
</TEXT>
