<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A hefty premium in the new Footsie futures contract was cut back
significantly yesterday after a large deal went through the market shortly
after the start of official trading, writes Peter John.
Dealers said that some Pounds 230m was shifted from gilts into equities via
the futures market towards the close of trading late on Monday. The trade
was attributed to either SG Warburg or Goldman Sachs. It was partly
responsible for topping up the futures contract for March expiry and keeping
it strong in after-hours' dealing.
Yesterday morning, the 'i's and 't's of the deal were still being dotted and
crossed, and finalisation was responsible for lifting the underlying market
initially.
However, the successful shift of cash coincided with some disappointing
trade statistics which provided an opportunity for investors to take profits
after the second 300-point rally within six months. The first rally was
followed by a 100-point fall and chart analysts obsessed with the idea that
history always repeats itself are looking for a similar consolidation.
March opened at 3,400 and hit a high of 3,408 before beginning to drift back
to 3,367 by the official close. The premium above the cash market narrowed
from around 30 points to 22 by the close, not far off its fair value
premium, which is calculated at about 18.
Footsie options saw buying of the March series, which pushed implied
volatility to around 13.5 per cent, compared with 12.5 per cent in the
January's. Total turnover of 37,336 lots was up from Monday's 31,594. Hanson
was the most heavily traded stock option with 1,827 lots dealt.
</TEXT>
