<DATE>931222
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / World Stock Markets: Poland outstrips emerging markets -
Companies are about to capitalise on Warsaw's boom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
While emerging market strategists debate the appeal of Asia, or Latin
America, Polish equities have left more conventional choices far behind this
year.
The Warsaw Stock Exchange has seen an almost uninterrupted boom since last
Easter, taking the WIG index up from 1,040.7 at the end of last year to
11,354.6 yesterday, up 433.6 or 4 per cent on the day, and indicating gains
of 991 and 718 per cent in local currency, and dollar terms respectively.
The process has taken the recent return to government of former communists
and their allies in its stride and share prices are expected to continue on
the upgrade, at least for the early months of 1994.
Mr Marek Borowski, Poland's finance minister and deputy premier responsible
for the economy, has told investors that the government intends to give a
top priority to privatisation through public share issues.
In another confidence bolstering move the prime minister, Mr Waldemar
Pawlak, has reaffirmed the promise that capital gains would remain untaxed,
as planned by his predecessors, until the end of 1995.
With continuing strong demand from domestic investors, Warsaw is still
capable of weekly gains of 10 per cent on some shares, in spite of a
slowdown last month. Now quoting 22 stocks, its ability to soak up new
offerings was demonstrated by a recent public offer of 30.1 per cent of the
equity in Bank Slaski.
The bank, one of the nine state owned banks being sold off under the
government's bank privatisation programme, saw a massive oversubscription
with over 800,000 applicants offering 7,993.2bn zlotys (Dollars 372m) for
1,226.5bn zlotys worth of shares. The 500,000 zloty offer price should more
than treble when the bank is first quoted on the WSE in the new year.
There were many, effectively multiple applications. Nevertheless the Bank
Slaski offer should lead to a major increase in the 200,000 or so investors
who already have accounts with the country's 36 stockbrokers.
In fact, the increased volume of business engendered by the offer threatens
to swamp the brokers and means that the WSE has been forced to postpone the
introduction of additional sessions until the second quarter of 1994.
However, the numbers mean that the exchange, which reopened after a break of
52 years in April 1991, is firmly entrenched. 'Its development cannot be
reversed' says Mr Wieslaw Rozlucki, the WSE chairman, commenting on the
implications of the new centre left government.
Small investors have rushed to buy shares this year and the underlying
stocks, on an average p/e ratio of 36, are 20 to 30 per cent overvalued
according to one foreign analyst.
However, the market is becoming increasingly sophisticated. Financial
reporting is developing in newpapers and newletters, and information on
Polish stocks is being put out by foreign brokers like Smith New Court and
the Italian-owned IMI Securities. Creditanstalt, the Austrian bank, which
has just opened the first foreign-owned broking house in Warsaw, is also
producing copious reports.
Foreign investors, expected to bring a measure of stability to the exchange
and accounting for 25 per cent of the stock ownership and 10 per cent of
daily trading according to Mr Rozlucki, have drawn back a little as they
wait for the bubble to burst.
But there is also the prospect of more foreign input. The Pioneer First
Polish Trust Fund, owned by the Boston-based Pioneer Group, has net current
assets worth Dollars 350m of which one-third has been invested on the WSE.
Turnover slowed in November as investors accumulated funds for the Bank
Slaski offer. That channelled funds into the treasury, but now the exchange
faces its first test as a provider of capital to the corporate sector as
companies already quoted plan rights issues and private companies consider
going public.
This month sees a 500m zlotys rights issue from the Export Development Bank
while Exbud, a construction company, and Swarzedz, a furniture producer,
have already announced new share issues. The privately owned Kredyt Bank is
planning to float its equity in the middle of next year, and become the
fifth bank to be quoted on the WSE.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>PLZ  Poland, East Europe.
</CN>
