<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Cheap power deal clears way for
NZ aluminium expansion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WELLINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Comalco and Sumitomo, owners of the Bluff aluminium smelter, New Zealand's
biggest industrial complex, are planning a NZDollars 300m (Pounds 113m)
expansion following this week's controversial decision by the government to
continue to give the smelter cheap power till 2012.
A Radio New Zealand report said that under the new contract Comalco will pay
substantially less than the city of Auckland, which has a population of 1m
and uses an equivalent amount of power.
The Dominion newspaper reported yesterday that the decision to approve the
deal struck between state owned electricity company Electricorp and Comalco
had split the cabinet.
The minority Alliance Party, pledged to support the government, which has a
very small majority, expressed disquiet at the decision.
The Dominion said the decision was pushed through by the prime minister, Mr
Jim Bolger, and the finance minister, Mr Bill Birch, after a long debate. A
number of other ministers expressed concern about the uncertainty of energy
supplies and wanted the contract renegotiated.
Ms Jeannette Fitzsimmons, an Alliance spokesperson, said that the smelter
was New Zealand's single biggest industrial user of electricity, taking 15
per cent. She said that the contract expired in the same year that New
Zealand was due to take the last gas from its large offshore Maui field. 'It
means New Zealand will probably have to switch to coal generation at a time
when the world will be increasingly concerned at emission problems,' she
said.
Comalco's managing director, Mr Kerry McDonald, said that the price and
continuity of supply would permit the company to go ahead with the expansion
. He said however that a final decision to expand rested with Comalco and
Sumitomo.
