<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: London copper prices climb to
3-month highs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Copper's price rose strongly again on the London Metal Exchange yesterday,
moving to its highest level for three months. In the past three trading days
the cost of copper for delivery in three months has risen by 6 per cent, or
Dollars 103.25, to Dollars 1,802.50 a tonne.
The price rose Dollars 35 yesterday in the thin, pre-Christmas market and
traders and analysts remained split about its prospects. 'The overall
fundamentals of this market still remain bearish, although sentiment is
currently being helped by the recent drawdown in LME stocks,' said Mr Angus
MacMillan, research manager at Billiton-Enthoven Metals, part of the Royal
Dutch/Shell group. 'However, the decline in stocks is likely to prove a
temporary phenomenon and has been attributed to delayed shipments from the
Commonwealth of Independent States and light Chinese offtake. US demand for
copper has improved but this is not enough on its own to prompt a turnaround
in sentiment in this market.'
But, according to Mr Wiktor Bielski of Bain and Company, part of the
Deutsche Bank Group, 'the fundamentals in the copper market are getting
better all the time'. He cited US copper demand - up 8 per cent so far in
1993 - and falls in copper stocks on both the New York Commodity Exchange
and the LME. Stocks represented only eight weeks' consumption, the lowest
ever coming out of a recession, he pointed out.
There had probably been a 1.5 per cent increase in western world copper
demand this year, compared with 1992, and 'people are begining to realise
there will not be a big surge in supply in 1994'. Mr Bielski said that only
60,000 to 70,000 tonnes of extra annual copper capacity was scheduled for
next year - the big surge was to be expected in 1995.
Nevertheless, in the short term he expected profit-taking temporarily to
halt copper's upward climb at between 82 cents a pound (Dollars 1,807.25 a
tonne) and 84 cents (Dollars 1,851.36).
