<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / International Capital Markets: Ministry acts to boost
Japan's finance markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Japanese Ministry of Finance yesterday announced a package of easing
regulations for the domestic securities markets in an attempt to bolster
Japan's ailing financial markets.
The 70-point package includes the resumption of rights issues, which have
been suspended since March 1990 when the Tokyo stockmarket started its
descent.
The announcement follows a 3.6 per cent fall in the Nikkei average on
Monday. Officials hope that rights issues by blue chip companies will help
attract investors to the sluggish Tokyo stockmarket.
Mr Minoru Nagaoka, president of the Tokyo stock exchange, said the share
offerings should be limited to companies ready to return profits to
shareholders.
The package includes an easing of investment curbs and simplification of
administrative procedures required of brokers.
Investment trust funds will be allowed to invest in interest rate and
currency swaps, lend out securities and borrow short-term funds. The ceiling
imposed on investment trust funds' investments in the unsecured call money
market will be lifted.
The ministry will also abolish the 'lock up' period for Euroyen bonds issued
by sovereign borrowers starting on January 1. To protect the country's
domestic corporate bond market, the ministry has prohibited Euroyen bonds
from entering the country for the first 90 days of issuance.
Japanese securities houses found their way around the restriction by
agreeing to 'warehouse' the bonds for three months before selling the paper
to Japanese investors. Market participants have been calling for the ban to
be lifted. The rule, however, remains for bonds issued overseas by Japanese
borrowers and overseas companies.
For the corporate bond market, the ministry eased eligibility standards for
issuing foreign and domestic yen bonds by Japanese companies to a minimum
credit rating of triple-B from single-A.
The ministry also confirmed there were no restrictions on the issuing of
dual-currency bonds, and floating rate notes.
</TEXT>
