<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / International Bonds: Italy to raise Y300bn in new year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE and HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Republic of Italy plans to raise Y300bn in the international bond market
early in the new year. The mandate for the widely-expected offering has been
awarded jointly to Daiwa and J. P. Morgan.
Yesterday's announcement coincided with the Japanese finance ministry's
decision to abolish the 'lock-up' period for Euroyen bonds issued by
sovereign borrowers from January 1. The lifting of this selling restriction
will facilitate the distribution of Eurobonds to investors in Japan.
Mr Alberto Giovannini, head of the Italian treasury's international
borrowing programme, said the timing of the Euroyen offering stemmed from
the virtual completion of the 1994 budget process in the Italian parliament
and the strength of the yen and the Japanese bond market. Italy has raised
about Dollars 12.8bn this year, within the Dollars 10bn-Dollars 15bn range
indicated 12 months ago as a target for 1993.
Daiwa said Italy's deal was likely to be the largest-ever offering of yen
securities outside the Japanese government bond market. No further details
were available yesterday but there was a view in the market that Italy was
looking for a maturity of more than five years.
Elsewhere, Woody Gundy pulled two more Canadian dollar offerings out of the
hat which allowed it to overtake ScotiaMcLeod in the Canadian dollar league
table.
Bayerische Landesbank raised Dollars 250m through an offering of Eurobonds
with a maturity of just under six years. One aim of the deal was to
re-finance a CDollars 75m five-year Eurobond offering which matured on
Monday. Part of the proceeds of yesterday's deal was swapped into floating
rate dollars.
The bonds were priced to yield 25 basis points over Canadian treasuries and
when they were freed to trade the spread remained intact.
Wood Gundy said the borrower took a good portion of the bonds to meet demand
from its retail clients.
Standard &amp; Poor's, the international rating agency, has raised its implied
rating of Chile's long-term foreign currency debt to triple B plus from
triple B.
</TEXT>
