FT  22 DEC 93 / International Capital Markets: Philadelphia SE rejects CBoE
merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Philadelphia Stock Exchange has rejected the Chicago Board Options
Exchange's bid for a merger, choosing for the third time in as many years to
remain independent.
The CBoE is reported to have bid Dollars 60m for the tiny exchange, which is
known for its foreign currency and equity options products.
The CBoE, the world's largest options exchange, made the offer for the Phlx
in early November. 'The CBoE is disappointed that the Phlx has rejected our
offer,' said Mr Alger 'Duke' Chapman, CBoE chairman.
'We are convinced that in these rapidly changing times that the two
exchanges would be stronger together than apart.'
Mr Chapman said his exchange maintained a co-operative relationship with the
Phlx, and had left the door open for further merger discussions.
