<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / International Company News: McDonnell Douglas settles C-17
dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
McDonnell Douglas, the US defence and aerospace group, said yesterday that
it had accepted a Pentagon plan to resolve a long-running dispute over
development of its controversial C-17 military transport aircraft.
The company will take a pre-tax charge of some Dollars 450m in the fourth
quarter to cover the settlement. There will be no significant adverse cash
impact.
The Pentagon revealed the outlines of the settlement on December 15, when it
placed McDonnell Douglas on 'probation'. The Pentagon said that unless the
company improved the performance of the C-17 programme, which has been
plagued by problems, it would buy only 40 of the aircraft, instead of the
120 planned.
As part of the settlement, McDonnell Douglas has dropped about Dollars 1.2bn
in claims against the government. The company announced last October that
the settlement would probably mean a Dollars 450m charge.
</TEXT>
