<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / International Company News: Alcoa to take Dollars 70m charge
in fourth quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Alcoa, North America's largest aluminium producer, is to take a Dollars 70m,
or 80 cents a share, after-tax charge against earnings in the fourth quarter
of 1993. It has also announced its fifth round of job reductions in 20
months.
The company said Dollars 59.4m of the fourth-quarter charge is associated
with the cost of permanent lay-offs of 1,600 hourly and salaried employees
in its US aluminium operations. Some of the reductions have already occurred
and the balance will be complete in 1994.
The remaining Dollars 10.8m of the charge stems from closing several
production operations, including an aluminium rod plant in Rockdale, Texas.
Alcoa is one of the few US aluminium producers to have remained profitable
in the face of a world aluminium glut and sharply depressed prices.
The company had third quarter earnings of Dollars 28.8m, or 32 cents a
share, on sales of Dollars 2.2bn.
</TEXT>
