<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / UK Company News: Eurotherm's 38% advance to Pounds 20.1m
helped by cost cuts and growth in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eurotherm, the industrial process control equipment supplier, turned in a 38
per cent increase in pre-tax profits for the year to October 31, buoyed by
improved productivity, higher margins and the positive impact of currency
movements.
Pre-tax profits were up from Pounds 14.6m to Pounds 20.1m, on turnover which
edged ahead by 2.5 per cent to Pounds 158.4m (Pounds 154.6m), mainly
reflecting growth in the US market.
Earnings per share rose by 35 per cent, from 22.3p to 30.2p. An increased
final of 6p is recommended, making a total for the year of 9.5p (8p).
Shares in the group, which is also proposing a 1-for-1 scrip issue to
improve liquidity, closed 16p ahead at 690p.
Tight control on costs, including a further reduction in the workforce to
2,030, and a renewed focus on profitable product sales, helped boost gross
profit margins by almost 2 percentage points. As a result operating profits
increased by 29 per cent to Pounds 20.1m.
The group, which derives an increasing proportion of its turnover from
outside the UK - over 65 per cent in the latest period - also benefited from
sterling's relative weakness against the dollar.
If 1992 figures are restated at 1993 exchange rates and disposals are
excluded, like-for-like turnover slipped by 2.6 per cent and pre-tax profits
expanded by 30 per cent.
Growth from the group's range of AC drives helped offset lower turnover from
process automation and the effects of the recession in Germany and France.
Net interest costs fell to Pounds 25,000 (Pounds 1.03m) reflecting the
group's strong Pounds 14.2m (Pounds 8.2m) cash generation, including a sharp
Pounds 3m reduction in stock levels, which enabled it to eliminate net
borrowings and end the period with cash balances of Pounds 6.8m.
COMMENT
Over the past three years Eurotherm's management has refocused the business
and introduced more profitable products while driving costs down and
introducing tighter financial controls. As a result most of the group's key
performance measures, including its return on capital, have improved
substantially. While there is still some scope for margin improvement,
future performance will mostly depend on the group's ability to grow
organically - despite the lack of any general upswing. This will mostly be
achieved through new products like the AC drives and expanded recorder
product range which will add about Pounds 7m to sales in the current year.
Pre-tax profits should reach Pounds 25m this year producing earnings of
about 37.7p. The shares, which have more than tripled in price over the past
three years, are now trading on a forward multiple of 18.3 - but still look
like a good buy.
</TEXT>
