<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / UK Company News: Wessex Water advances 21% - Acquisitions
and organic growth boost waste management activity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Wessex Water brought the reporting season for the 10 privatised water
companies to a close with better than expected results showing a 21 per cent
increase in interim pre-tax profits and a 10 per cent increase in the
dividend.
Mr Nicholas Hood, chairman, attributed the strong profits growth, from
Pounds 44.3m to Pounds 53.4m, to tight control of costs, which, excluding
depreciation and infrastructure maintenance, have not risen for the last two
years. Sales rose by 6 per cent to Pounds 109m for the six months to
September 30.
Fully diluted earnings per share were depressed by the Pounds 144.5m rights
issue in January, falling from 31.6p to 31.4p. The interim dividend is
raised to 8p (7.3p).
There was a strong performance from Wessex Waste Management, the joint
venture with Waste Management International, which increased its
contribution from Pounds 1.6m to Pounds 4.2m. Mr Hood said the sharp
increase was because of both acquisitions and organic growth. Five
businesses had been acquired since the previous year for Pounds 7m,
contributing turnover of about Pounds 15m to the operation's total sales
which doubled to Pounds 42.1m.
Wessex Waste Management intended to continue pursuing acquisitions, Mr Hood
said, and had Pounds 80m with which to fund expansion.
The core utility side improved profits by 19 per cent, with just 6
percentage points due to price increases. The rest had been down to cost
controls, Mr Hood said. These included a small reduction in jobs through
natural wastage and strict control of fuel costs and other overheads.
Mr Hood said he was confident the company would achieve a satisfactory
settlement in next year's review of pricing by Ofwat, the regulator.
'We have got an amazing efficiency programme which I know is recognised by
Ofwat,' he said. 'I am confident we will get as good a deal as anybody.'
However, there was likely to an element of negotiating. 'You will always end
up with some eyeballing.'
Wessex has capital spending requirements of Pounds 120m in the current year
and about Pounds 100m is targeted for 1994.
The group ended the first half with net cash of Pounds 53m, against Pounds
54m at the start of the year. Mr Hood said he expected the group to have no
borrowings at the end of the current year.
</TEXT>
