<PROFILE>_AN-DLVCCAD5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931222
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / UK Company News: Telegraph may buy into The Independent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The board of Newspaper Publishing, publisher of The Independent and the
Independent on Sunday, gave the go-ahead yesterday for talks on a possible
new minority shareholder.
A number of potential investors ranging from Mr Conrad Black's Hollinger
group, which controls The Daily Telegraph, Lord Rothermere's Associated
Newspapers and Mr Michael Green, chairman of Carlton Communications, have
expressed interest.
Mr Richard Branson, chairman of the Virgin Group, has also expressed an
informal interest.
The board yesterday approved in principle a three-year business plan drawn
up by Mr Patrick Morrissey, the recently appointed chief executive.
The plan is designed to rejuvenate the papers, which have suffered
significant circulation loss over the past six months.
Mr Morrissey last week made it clear that the aim was to approve the
business plan and then go forward to arrange new financing for the company.
After the board meeting the company said: 'A number of different options
were examined which would allow a secure future to emerge from the
restructuring process now being undertaken.'
The statement continued: 'Considerable progress has been made and a further
statement will be made early in the new year.'
The options being considered range from raising necessary finance from
existing shareholders through a rights issue through to bringing in a new
minority shareholder to a full takeover by rival newspaper publishers.
The leading option at the moment is bringing in a national newspaper
proprietor to take a 20 per cent to 30 per cent stake.
Mr Black is the most likely candidate if a way can be found of ringfencing
the editorial independence of the titles.
</TEXT>
