<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Wood gets flotation option: RBS joint venture could be sold
if market value exceeds Pounds 200m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Peter Wood, chief executive of Direct Line, the motor and household
insurer, will be allowed to float a new insurance joint venture with Royal
Bank of Scotland if it reaches a market value of Pounds 200m.
Mr Wood will have the choice of full or partial flotation of the company,
which will insure 'non-standard' risks such as young drivers. He will have
the right to buy out Royal Bank's 60 per cent stake if it does not want a
flotation.
The deal follows speculation that Royal Bank might float Direct Line itself,
which analysts have estimated could be worth more than Pounds 1bn.
Speculation has eased since the recent strong rise in Royal Bank's share
price.
Details of the deal between Mr Wood, who was paid an Pounds 18m bonus by
Royal Bank this year and an additional Pounds 24m to buy out his bonus
arrangement, were disclosed in a letter to shareholders. They will be asked
to approve the buy-out of Mr Wood's bonus scheme and the new joint venture
at the annual meeting on January 14.
Mr Wood is to invest Pounds 1m in the new venture, giving him a 40 per cent
equity stake.
The bank also revealed in its annual report and accounts that remuneration
of directors had risen sharply as a result of the bank's increase in pre-tax
profits to Pounds 265.2m, against Pounds 12.6m for the year to September
1992.
The remuneration of Mr George Mathewson, Royal Bank's chief executive, has
risen 55 per cent from Pounds 219,287 to Pounds 341,326, while that of Lord
Younger, its chairman, has advanced 33 per cent to Pounds 167,814.
Total performance-related bonuses of executive directors - excluding Mr
Wood's - rose to Pounds 971,000 from Pounds 160,000, while pension
contributions went up to Pounds 473,000 from Pounds 246,000, and other
emoluments to Pounds 183,000 from Pounds 100,000.
The bank's 22,000 UK staff will be paid a 5.1 per cent bonus from a
profit-sharing scheme in January.
Mr Wood will be non-executive chairman of the new insurance venture - in
which Royal Bank is investing Pounds 1.5m in equity capital and Pounds 22.5m
in preference shares - and will be allowed to spend up to a day a week
working on it.
The deal stipulates that if a merchant bank values the new company above
Pounds 200m, Mr Wood may choose a full or partial flotation. If Royal Bank
does not agree, he will have the right to buy out its preference and
ordinary shares.
It also says that if the new company requires additional capital which Royal
Bank is not prepared to supply, then Mr Wood can provide the additional
funds himself, or through a third party, and buy out the bank's equity
stake.
</TEXT>
