<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Yeltsin announces abolition of Russia's security ministry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Boris Yeltsin last night announced the abolition of Russia's
Ministry of Security - formerly the KGB - in a move which brings the
country's security and intelligence services under his direct control.
A new federal counter-intelligence service has been created, with its
director explicitly under Mr Yeltsin's command. The director retains
ministerial status but is no longer in the cabinet.
Mr Nikolai Golushko, the current security minister, has been named director
of the service and given only two weeks to present a proposal for the
reorganisation.
The move comes after Mr Yeltsin criticised the ministry for failing to warn
of the armed uprising staged by the former parliament in October. It follows
the gains made by the Liberal Democratic party of Mr Vladimir Zhirinovsky in
the recent elections. Many of the party's leading members are former
security officers, and it is routinely accused of being a creation of the
KGB since its foundation in 1990.
Security agents are temporarily retained on staff, but only until they take
a test which almost certainly will require proof of their loyalty to the
president.
The abolition of the ministry was presented as the death of a service which
was powerful and feared in Tsarist times, which became a vast empire of
terror and suppression under the communists. A statement from the
president's office said that in its various forms - as Cheka, NKVD and KGB -
the security police had 'proved unreformable'.
It said: 'Attempts to re-organise it in the past were superficial and
unsuccessful. At the present time, the security ministry has no concept of
Russia's state security needs. The counter intelligence system has been
weakened, while the system of political police has been preserved and can
easily be recreated.
'On the landscape of the democratic transformation going on in Russia, the
system of providing security has outlived itself, is ineffective, is a heavy
burden on the state budget and is a barrier to economic reform.'
The reshuffle does not affect the foreign counter-intelligence service,
which was separated from the KGB last year, and is now headed by Mr Yevgeny
Primakov, a former aide to President Mikhail Gorbachev.
Another former Gorbachev aide and liberal politburo member, Mr Alexander
Yakovlev, was yesterday named as head of the main Ostankino state television
channel, following the sacking of Mr Vyacheslav Bragin, seen in presidential
circles as the man who handed the election to Mr Zhirinovsky. Mr Yakovlev
has supported the Russia's Choice political group.
Yeltsin hint of new economic course Page 4
</TEXT>
<XX>
