<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / The Lex Column: Wessex Water
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It was hard luck that Wessex chose to release its interim figures on the day
the latest bull run in water shares came to an end. A 20 per cent increase
in pre-tax profits and a 10 per cent dividend increase were hardly excuses
for yesterday's sell-off in the sector. Holding operating costs steady in
the regulated water business for the third year running, due to the
introduction of flexible working practices and performance related pay, is
especially impressive. Yet it is the success of Wessex's joint venture in
waste management that underpins the dividend. A doubling of half-year
profits in waste is a welcome contrast to the red ink being spilt elsewhere
in the sector. That said, the heady pace of acquisitions - another five were
completed in the last six months - makes the underlying progress difficult
to judge. Without an improvement in landfill prices, any margin gains will
be hard won.
With cash still in hand from January's rights issue, Wessex could easily
finance its portion of another large acquisition in waste. If the prospects
are as good as it says, it would do well to move sooner rather than later.
Keeping rights money in the bank at current rates of interest will do
nothing to improve earnings per share.
</TEXT>
