<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / UK's trade gap with non-EU countries widens to Pounds 767m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's visible trade gap with countries outside the European Union more
than doubled last month after a sharp drop in the value of exports.
The deficit with non-EU trading partners widened to Pounds 767m from
October's Pounds 372m. This followed a 7.5 per cent fall in export values
from Pounds 5.2bn to Pounds 4.8bn. Imports remained flat at Pounds 5.5bn.
Excluding oil and such erratic items as ships and aircraft - a more reliable
guide to the underlying trend - the deficit jumped from Pounds 386m to
Pounds 634m.
Although the widening of the trade gap looks alarming, it follows a small
deficit in October which government statisticians believed to be
unsustainable. Over the latest three months, the deficit appears to have
flattened. In the three months to November, the trade gap was just over
Pounds 2bn, the same as in the previous three-month period.
Mr Richard Needham, the trade minister, said the UK 'must look to future
opportunities in the Far East, India, South America and in Europe and the US
which are fast coming out of recession'.
But Mr Robin Cook, the shadow trade and industry secretary said that unless
the UK improved its ability to make and sell things in the world, recovery
would not be sustainable: 'If we are unable to compete in world markets now,
what is going to happen when GATT comes into force and competition hots up?'
Measured by volume and excluding oil and erratic items, exports and imports
continued their rise, but by only 0.5 per cent last month, compared with
over 1 per cent in October.
Exporters continued to increase prices substantially in November, in spite
of little movement in the value of the pound since the first quarter,
indicating that manufacturers are attempting to rebuild their profit margins
through export sales.
The Central Statistical Office said that in the three months to November
export prices increased by 12 per cent, compared with the previous three
months, against only a 4.5 per cent rise in import prices over the same
period.
The non-EU trade figures paint a different picture from the intra-EU
statistics. Yesterday's non-EU trade figures show import volumes rising a
seasonally adjusted 4 per cent in the three months to November, compared
with only a 1 per cent rise in underlying export volumes. The EU figures
suggest a relatively flat picture for imports.
The deficit on trade with the US and Canada was Pounds 74m compared with a
Pounds 130m surplus in October. In the latest three months the deficit was
Pounds 5m compared with a surplus of Pounds 183m in the three months to
August.
Exports to western European countries outside the EU reached a record Pounds
934m in November. However, over the latest three months they were down
slightly on the previous three-month period. The deficit held steady at just
above Pounds 1bn.
Exports of manufactured goods grew slightly faster than imports in the
latest three months, compared with the three months to August. Compared with
the same three months a year ago, exports of manufactured goods were up a
seasonally adjusted 27 per cent against an increase of 19 per cent for
imports.
</TEXT>
