FT  22 DEC 93 / Observer: Switched on
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
W Edwards Deming, who died this week, may have been one of the most
influential figures in modern industrial management, but that is not what
sticks in the mind of one of Observer's colleagues. His enduring memory is
of a conference in Detroit where an awe-struck audience became increasingly
puzzled by a rambling and somewhat disjointed speech by Deming, then in his
70s.
It was not until question time that the man who taught the Japanese Total
Quality Management admitted to having been beaten by one of life's simpler
challenges.
He had not been able to read his prepared text because he could not figure
out how to switch on the light on the lectern.
