FT  22 DEC 93 / Observer: Well matched
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir John Banham's Local Government Commission is always being attacked for
its lack of clear direction, so the government deserves some credit for its
imaginative choice of new commissioners.
Chris Chope, a former minister and before that leader of Tory flag-waving
Wandsworth borough council, has been paired with Margaret Hodge, former
leader of Islington borough council (no Tory councillors at all at the last
election). Both are undeniable local government heavyweights, unlike the
other commissioners, and have a public stature to rival Sir John's.
Chope has a reputation for attacking unnecessary costs in local government -
a subject dear to Sir John's heart - while Hodge is a veteran of numerous
rows with the government over poll tax capping. Hard to believe that this
deadly combination will help the commission's increasingly disobedient
chairman toe the government's party line.
