FT  22 DEC 93 / Observer: Gear change from BMW
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
When the marketing supremo of the German car industry handed in his notice a
couple of weeks ago, his associates at BMW sat heavily on speculation that
Robert Buchelhofer was headed for Audi or any of Germany's other
hard-pressed carmakers.
Indeed he is not. From February, the 51-year-old Austrian will be on the
starting blocks of a brand new career, as a partner at the Frankfurt offices
of TASA International, the Swiss-based headhunting network.
Gabriele Willner, one of his new colleagues, claims he decided about a year
ago that he had peaked in the motor trade - just when BMW was crowing about
having outsold arch-rival Mercedes for the first time.
It was also when Bernd Pischetsrieder, group production director and just
45, was being presented to BMW's supervisory board as the man to succeed
chairman Eberhard von Kuenheim.
Unusual as it may be for German executives to undertake such dramatic career
switches, there comes a point when some say 'I've had it with this job and
stupid supervisory boards', Willner notes diplomatically.
She herself marketed Lancaster cosmetics in an earlier life, while other
TASA International partners in Germany come from retailing or the drinks
business.
Willner confides that the new recruit will be helped from 0 to 90 with
searches for two motor industry scalps, but that he will be expected to be
up to speed in all fields before long.
</TEXT>
