<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Leading Article: Local difficulties
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
When the Local Government Commission was launched in June 1992, ministers
expressed the hope that it would settle the structure of local government in
England for decades to come. That hope looks increasingly forlorn, with
little coherence in the commission's recommendations and continuing
ministerial interference in its work. Now comes the threat of a revolt by
backbench Tory MPs, concerned over the upheaval and its attendant costs.
The commission has been flawed from the start by its presumption that
opinion polls are an appropriate tool for deciding local government
structures. Its initial proposals were based on polls about people's
feelings about their local identity. In most cases, those proposals proved
unpopular and have had to be substantially revised. In trying to please
everybody, the commission has predictably ended up satisfying nobody.
It is not yet clear whether the revised plans will be more palatable to
local opinion. However, business leaders have already reacted with horror to
plans to create small single-tier authorities in areas such as Bristol and
Middlesbrough. They believe that wider strategic local government is needed
for urban areas such as these, which reach out beyond the city boundaries to
the larger economic areas around them.
Ministers argue that single-tier unitary authorities will cut administrative
costs and be more accountable than the present two-tier structure. Yet if
unitary authorities are smaller than counties, they will multiply the
administrative costs of county services. And if they are too small to
provide strategic services such as police and fire services, these will pass
to quangos and joint boards which are much less accountable than elected
councils.
There is a case for single unitary authorities for special cases such as the
Isle of Wight. Some larger cities such as Bristol, Leicester and Southampton
might also function better as unitary authorities - like the old county
boroughs abolished in the 1974 local government reorganisation. But in much
of England outside the conurbations, a two-tier system is needed if local
government is to think strategically yet deliver services responsively.
Recognising this would allow the government to restrict the work of the
commission to authorities where there is overwhelming local support for
change.
There are, in any case, much more important tasks than drawing lines on maps
in search of a chimerical perfect structure. One is the problem of making
the quangos which provide an increasing share of local public services more
accountable to their customers. Ministers, alas, show no interest in this
subject. It is time they reined in the Local Government Commission and
switched agendas.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
