<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Leading Article: Bombay scam
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Everybody was to blame, especially foreigners. This is the conclusion of
yesterday's report from the Indian parliamentary committee which
investigated last year's securities scandal. Its description of how easily
money flowed out of the banking system into the stock market in flagrant
violation of banking and stock exchange regulations will make many people
feel uncomfortable. None of those involved are spared from criticism. The
report is particularly tough on the finance ministry and the Bombay stock
exchange. Foreign banks, it says, were the 'originators and also the biggest
players'.
Many of its conclusions are self-evident. It is clear that there was
systemic laxity in oversight of financial markets. However, the report errs
in suggesting the scandal was the result of liberalisation of financial
markets. It was precisely because of official attempts to control the money
markets that institutions with money on deposit at low, regulated rates
sought methods of earning a better return, including portfolio management
schemes offered by foreign banks. If interest rates were liberalised, the
temptation to circumvent control would not exist. India needs better
supervision, but fewer rules.
That central bank restrictions were violated has been admitted by several
foreign banks. That internal controls of some banks were lax is clear.
Standard Chartered of the UK has shuffled managers, dispensed with some
staff in India and reported a Pounds 305m loss from its Indian operations in
1992. Nor can foreign banks suggest this was a purely Indian problem in
which they were hapless victims. Their international expertise helped them
to dominate the inter-bank securities markets in which most irregularities
occurred. The committee's suggestion that banks broke laws of their own
countries deserves thorough investigation.
As for the treatment to be meted out in India to the foreign banks, the
committee is right to suggest that a country seen consistently to uphold
rules will attract foreign investors rather than deter them. However,
suspension or expulsion would send the wrong signal when India's reforms are
seeking to break down barriers to the outside world. It would suggest
renewed insularity and xenophobia, as well as an unwillingness to tackle the
true inadequacies of the financial system. It takes more than one party to
make a scandal: many Indian banks have changed top managers as a result of
the scam, and a number of once-prominent people face criminal charges.
The scandal will have been of benefit if it forces Indian regulators into
more effective supervision. What is most important, however, is that this
should take place against a background of further liberalisation. India's
hopes lie in greater openness, not in a return to bashing foreigners.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>INZ  India, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
