<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Letters to the Editor: Gaidar's Russia - the dangers
inherent in 'shock therapy'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Prof ALAN W CAFRUNY and Mr MAURICE GLASMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, We note with interest your description of Yegor Gaidar's 'Russia's
Choice' party as 'the voice of reason' ('Gaidar calls for anti-fascist
front', December 14). In the aftermath of the elections Gaidar is certainly
correct to draw a parallel between the strong showing of neo-fascists and
developments in Weimar Germany.
Many Russians believe, however, that Gaidar's draconian reforms represent an
'economic Versailles'. Under strong pressure from the west, the Yeltsin
government has made deep cuts in the state budget and in subsidies to heavy
industry as well as to consumers. These cuts have contributed to the
impoverishment of millions, and the crippling of the welfare state,
including the virtual collapse of health services.
Some of the consequences of these policies were cited in a recent report,
The Distributional Consequences of Russia's Transition, by Dr Chris Doyle,
reported by the FT ('Pay gaps threaten to split Russia', October 14).
Between 1985 and 1991-92, real household wealth declined by 86 per cent and
incomes plunged by up to one-half. Many pensioners have seen their incomes
reduced to half of the official 'physiological minimum'. Privatisation is
not leading to a dispersion of income or wealth, but rather to the
'concentration of ownership into a few powerful institutions', such as
pension funds and conglomerates.
The message widely disseminated in the media and by influential economists
is that although these policies are regrettable, no other strategy can
secure a democratic transition from state planning to markets. Yet this
assumption runs counter to historical experience. After the second world
war, the economies of western Europe and Japan were gradually opened up
thanks to generous aid, state controls designed to maintain production and
employment; protectionism; and redistributive measures. These policies were
rightly seen not as impediments to fledgling market democracies, but as
essential components of them.
The losers of the cold war have been subject to harsher treatment. Economic
reform is surely a prerequisite of democracy, but only if it is acceptable
to the Russian people. The resort to 'shock therapy' as a means of social
engineering is no less dogmatic, and no less antithetical to democracy, than
the blind faith of Soviet commissars in the state to which it bears more
than a passing resemblance. The election results should encourage the west
to reconsider its policies towards the east as well as to the institutional
realities of economic success in the west.
Alan W Cafruny,
professor of international
relations,
Maurice Glasman,
research fellow,
European University Institute
Via dei Roccettini, 9,
50016 San Domenico di Fiesole (Florence), Italy
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
