<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Arts: The Tale of Tsar Saltan - Opera in Berlin
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW CLARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
While fairy tales have become a welcome part of the Christmas diet for
British opera companies, most German theatres are too blinkered to venture
beyond Hansel und Gretel. That may explain why Rimsky-Korsakov's The Tale of
Tsar Saltan has been so well received at the Komische Oper in Berlin. With
its Cinderella-like characters and exotic musical pictures, Tsar Saltan
deserves to be better known. This was its Berlin premiere.
Like so much of the Komische Oper's repertory, the work was performed in a
'Neufassung' - in other words, it was doctored to suit the way Harry Kupfer
wanted to stage it. Tsar Saltan emerged mercifully unscathed. Kupfer cut
some of the obscure corners of a circuitous plot, but otherwise preserved
its charm and humour.
Reinhart Zimmermann's decor captured the stuffy, snowy atmosphere of the
Tsar's court as effectively as the sunny freedom of the paradise to which
the heroine Militrisa and her son Guidon were banished. Reinhard Heinrich's
costumes were colour-coded - pink and purple for the court, blue and green
for the desert island - which made their coming together for the final scene
a visual symbol of harmony. The production was naive in the best sense of
the word.
Sabine Passow was the blonde and gracious Militrisa, Donald George a
bright-eyed, bright-voiced tenor prince. Hans-Martin Nau's dopey Tsar made
up in blundering comedy what he lacked in largesse. The company showed off
its depth and experience in the ensemble scenes, but some parts - notably
the Swan-Princess - were poorly sung. One expects as much at the Komische
Oper, where dramatic expression has always been more highly prized than
musical purity. What was not expected was the quality of orchestral playing
under the young Australian conductor Simone Young. The audience loved every
minute. And so did I.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
