<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Arts: It is all a question of taste - Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Poor little French television producers and film directors: great big Yankee
bullies are forcing unwilling Frenchmen to sit down and watch Hill Street
Blues and coralling them into cinemas to watch Basic Instinct when all they
really wanted to do, left to their own devices, was luxuriate in French
television's literary marathon Apostrophe and watch exciting Jean Luc Godard
films? There there. Never mind, the exclusion of film and television
programmes from the new Gatt agreement will no doubt enable you to put a
stop to all that. If by some wild chance it does not, and your fellow
countrymen wilfully persist in watching Miami Vice and Terminator Treize you
will just have to pass a few laws banning Hitchcock movies and rationing
viewers to one American sitcom a week. To ensure they are doing as they are
told you may need to install home monitoring devices to watch all viewers as
they view. You could call this 'Grand Frere'.
Can there really be anybody in France, even the most heavily bearded,
thickly tweed jacketed, Gitane smoking director of art house movies, who
seriously believes that you can legislate for taste? Or is the idea to build
a cultural Berlin Wall to restrict the French to French culture and stop
them being seduced by another, more attractive? To ask such sarcastic
questions is not to imply that Shane is 'better' than The Three Musketeers
(though that is not inconceivable) or that The Golden Girls is superior to .
. . well, whatever the French equivalent may be. Significantly the French
equivalent has not exactly taken the world by storm, though that is not
because other countries have erected tariff barriers to exclude French
comedy. The sarcasm is prompted by the bizarre sight (whoops, sorry, cannot
have French words invading the English language - the peculiar sight) of an
ancient European culture attempting, at the end of the 20th century, to use
tariff barriers to stop its people experiencing a newer, younger, culture
which is seen to be (presumably, otherwise why all the anxiety?) more
powerful and more popular.
None of which is to deny sympathy for the protectionists' object; only for
their methods. Of course any intelligent viewer wants to see preserved and
even extended that part of the culture which is full of insight, beauty,
truth, enlightenment, joy, curiosity, revelation, and artistic sensibility
and not merely that which is entertaining, scandalous or shocking. Anyone
living in the UK, and especially in the capital city, during the past year
must have noticed the signs that, at least as far as television is
concerned, Britain is drifting, or perhaps steaming, in a similar direction.
Programmes on the ITV network in general and on Carlton, the new London
weekday station in particular, have been not so much slipping down market as
galloping. The network which used to bring us such serious current affairs
series as First Tuesday, This Week and Viewpoint now brings us The Big
Story, Blues And Twos ('See the old lady trapped under the lorry] Hear her
whimper]') and Hollywood Women which might have been better entitled
Hollywood Boobs.
It would be absurd to suggest that everything appearing on the old ITV was
magnificent and everything appearing on the new version is appalling. For
years the old ITV got away with screening Crossroads not once but twice and
even three times a week. Much of the embarrassing rubbish they show today
was developed under the old system: Blind Date, Beadle's About, Prisoner
Cell Block H and much more. Conversely, some of the programmes shown by ITV
in the past 12 months, whether from long established series or new ones,
have been excellent. The drama series that has just finished, All Or Nothing
At All, about a City charmer who tries to make others happy by providing 100
per cent per annum interest for his friends and colleagues, and then blows
all their investments on the horses was, by any reckoning, impressive.
Cracker was outstanding. A recent report by Trevor Phillips in The London
Programme, about black people systematically defrauding the social services,
and organised corruption among blacks in local government, was astonishing.
Had it been made by a white man it would never have been screened. Phillips
is a brave man.
But whatever the exceptions they are memorable because they do prove the
rule: that whereas the people in ITV used to be interested in competing with
the BBC for kudos as well as audiences, today their eyes are fixed
unswervingly on the ratings. Once upon a time when the BBC rejected The
Naked Civil Servant, declaring it untransmittable, Carlton's predecessor,
Thames TV, commissioned the drama and won worldwide admiration and shelves
full of awards. It is inconceivable that Carlton would do the same today:
even if someone inside the company recognised the quality and wanted to
commission the programme, the risk (which is to say the chance of failing to
make a large profit) would be too great. This indicates a radical and sad
change, due almost entirely to Thatcherite broadcasting legislation.
Tell that to today's ITV executives and they run their thumbs down the backs
of their Armani lapels, smile (you may say 'sneer' but I could not possibly
comment) and tell you that they simply do not make programmes for television
critics any more. This is their way of agreeing that considerations of
quality and prestige have now gone by the board and ratings are indeed the
sole criterion. And why is that? For a while they will try to maintain that
their only aim is to satisfy the largest possible number of viewers, but
later in the evening, when they become honest, they will admit that all that
really counts is making the largest possible amount of money. And why not?
Do not grocers and hairdressers maximise profits by satisfying as many
people as possible? Of course . . . as do drug dealers and prostitutes.
Perish the thought that one should compare ITV executives to such people,
but the idea that they are culturally neutral suppliers of services like
grocers or hairdressers is disingenuous.
Perhaps it does not matter; perhaps such a change is desirable. Rupert
Murdoch and others have always claimed that too many of the programmes on
British television, so obviously a mass medium, are made by middle class
trendies for middle class trendies. If ITV as a federal network (even though
it still includes companies such as Granada where quality counts for a lot)
continues to jettison its old high quality series and goes all out instead
for ratings using scandal, hypnosis shows, cringe-telly, ambulance chasing,
and big breasts, why should that matter? In a sense it does not. We tolerate
vulgar trash in newspapers, books, music and most areas of our culture and
nobody assumes that the hideous rubbish which comprises so much popular
music will somehow destroy Verdi operas or Beethoven symphonies. In this we
seem to differ from the French.
The important thing, surely, is to see that the cultural influences
available to us are wide ranging. The danger is that television is a very
young medium, still developing, and has not yet escaped from government
control. The baby could be lost with the bath water. So long as we continue
to have the BBC providing a full range of programmes, including those of
very high quality, perhaps it does not matter if ITV lowers its sights and
throws in its lot with the comics, paperbacks and pop concerts which
constitute so much of mass culture. It would certainly be both pathetic and
patronising to attempt to legislate for public taste a la Francais. But we
should be open and honest about what is happening. If ITV moves off
determinedly down market, so be it. We should note the move, plot it with
care, and take greater trouble than ever to sustain the BBC.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
