<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Business and the Environment: Wood out of waste
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID SPARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you eat a hamburger at McDonald's, you could be sitting at a table made
partly from waste polystyrene packaging and throwaway razors. Brothers
Andrew and Robert Billson have developed a process in the UK for blending
polystyrene wastes to make a hardwood substitute ready for immediate use
without further machining. McDonald's and the Alton Towers amusement park
are among their first customers.
The Billsons have cracked one of the main problems of recycling: how to
achieve a product valuable enough to cover the costs. Their Durawood sells
at a price comparable with that of hardwood after finishing. It never needs
painting, does not rot and resists insects.
Robert Billson, who took a degree in recycling, likens their
polystyrene-blending process to those he used when making alloys for cars
and aircraft from waste metal at the original Billson family company.
Andrew Billson was a shipwright's apprentice, before managing the fitting
out of shops, restaurants and the Heathrow Penta hotel. After coming across
some plastic wood made from polystyrene and using it to construct a picnic
table, he asked Robert to join him in setting up Savewood Products which is
based on the Isle of Wight.
Polystyrene in its crude state is denser than water, and pentane, an
inflammable gas, has widely been used to reduce its density. The Billsons
looked for something safer and found an agent which generates carbon
dioxide. As the plastic is drawn through an extruder to form lengths, carbon
dioxide bubbles inside are stretched, so they resemble the vessels in wood
and give a graining effect.
Wood made from polystyrene requires flame retardants, usually including
poisonous antimony trioxide, but the Billsons again found a safer
substitute. They also decided to colour their wood with iron oxide, rather
than organic or cadmium dyes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Savewood Products.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2511 Wood Household Furniture.
    P2519 Household Furniture, NEC.
</IN>
