<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / People: Plaistowe takes on APB
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Ian Plaistowe, a senior partner with accountants Arthur Andersen, is to
become chairman of the Auditing Practices Board, the standards-setting body
for auditors.
He will take over in April next year from Bill Morrison, who retired
recently as deputy chairman of KPMG Peat Marwick. Michael Boyd, a partner
with Ernst &amp; Young, is also resigning as vice chairman of the APB at the
same time, and will be replaced by Ian Percy, a partner with Grant Thornton.
Michael Chamberlain, chairman of the Consultative Committee of Accountancy
Bodies, which funds the APB, says he sees two roles for Plaistowe: 'The
first is to continue its programme of revising and tightening up existing
auditing standards and guidelines; the second is to look forward and deal
with the expectations and issues of the future.'
</TEXT>
