<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / People: EMAP's chair
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Stockbroker Graham Ross Russell, 60, who has been associated with media
group EMAP since the early 1960s, is to hand over the chairmanship to
Burton's chairman Sir John Hoskyns, 66, at the start of EMAP's financial
year next April.
It is over a year since Ross Russell, who has been chairman since 1990,
announced that he was looking for a successor. 'My real love is medium and
small companies,' says Ross Russell, who joined the board of Emap when it
was making profits of just Pounds 150,000.
He has not said whether he will retire from the EMAP board but indicates
that he does not think it is a good idea for ex-chairmen to remain,
especially when they had been on the board for 23 years.
Ross Russell says Sir John has been picked partly for his knowledge of large
companies, which he acquired during his stint as director general of the
Institute of Directors, and for his City connections. He is a director of
Clerical Medical &amp; General Life Assurance.
Although Sir John is reasonably old to be taking on another non-executive
chairmanship, Ross Russell says he 'does not act or appear his age'. Sir
John will be expected to spend 'one or two days' a week on EMAP business.
</TEXT>
