<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Management: Programmed for success - So you're thinking of
taking part in a business broadcast? Simon Ellis offers some guidance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON ELLIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When sizing up a possible appearance on a business programme there are four
important things you need to know: What is the audience? How big a ration of
airtime are you likely to get? How much of your time is going to be taken up
by filming/recording? And to what extent are the journalists/producers known
for putting their slant on the programme, giving interviewees a rough ride,
and heavy editing?
Broadly there are two types of factual programme. First there are the daily
news-driven variety which set out to report what is happening, offer
succinct analysis and look forward to what may be about to happen. Second,
there are weekly current affairs, documentary and investigative programmes
which often set out either to prove a thesis, make a point or nail a
villain.
The first may seem more enticing, but just because a programme appears
hard-hitting it does not mean you should avoid it. Also, satellite channels
should not be overlooked. They have lots of airtime needing to be filled
cheaply and are keen to get established in the potentially lucrative
business market.
Producers therefore need to persuade well-known business figures to be
interviewed reasonably often - . they cannot afford to upset interviewees by
roughing them up. Their lean resources mean they have to move quickly -
inconveniencing you less - and they lack time to attempt any severe editing.
The following, read in conjunction with the table, is a personal rating of
the best-known business broadcast slots.
MONEY PROGRAMME (BBC2). Its line will generally have been decided before
filming and, if necessary, will have been approved higher up the BBC's
editorial chain.
It is essential to be clear about exactly what story they are telling before
deciding whether to take part. Also, be clear about your role in the plot:
are you Expert? Pundit/Critic? Victim/Loser? Target/Baddie/Aggressor?
Running a stopwatch over two recent programmes showed that 14 of the 25
interviews lasted 30 seconds or less. In contrast, the reporter was speaking
for roughly 60-70 per cent of the report.
Bear in mind that the Money Programme, like other BBC current affairs
programmes, may consume much time in fixing locations and interviews. On the
plus side, it has the biggest UK audience for a business programme (1.3m
viewers). It is also the most upmarket of all BBC Television News and
Current Affairs programmes, beating Newsnight and Panorama with an audience
which is 26 per cent AB.
INVESTIGATIVE PROG-RAMMES, such as Watchdog and Checkpoint, are often fairly
entertainment driven. They need a strong storyline and preferably a clear
baddie to keep ratings and budget high. The higher the entertainment factor
and the stronger the goodies and baddies element, the more careful you must
be.
There is a built-in tendency to see things from the standpoint of the
consumer underdog rather than the corporate fat cat.
BUSINESS BREAKFAST (BBC1). Criticised for too many features, not enough City
news and too small an audience (average 300,000 at any moment), the show is
nevertheless beamed to Europe and Asia on World Service Television's growing
business output. Interviews are sometimes repackaged for later WSTV business
bulletins if relevant to overseas viewers.
You can expect a much better airtime ration than on the Money Programme. The
most benign slot is the chatty review of the business pages which normally
includes two appearances of up to three minutes each. Other items are of
similar length. Interviewing style is a mixture of chatty and formal, and
all straight down the line.
FINANCIAL WORLD TONIGHT (BBC Radio 4). The late transmission time limits the
audience (250,000), while the length (14 minutes) limits the number of
reports.
But the programme does offer the most comprehensive roundup of the day's UK
business news on British airwaves. It is a news-driven programme which does
not impose its own slant on events. Many reports use just a couple of clips.
Straight interviews last 2-3 minutes.
IN BUSINESS (BBC Radio 4). This programme has found that there is a craving
for coverage of management issues, trends and fads. It steers clear of the
City and economics and concentrates on the nuts and bolts of being in
business.
The programme is good at listening to interviewees and gives them time to
develop their point.
It gets a very good response from its audience (500,000 on Wednesday and
Sunday combined) - with up to 1,500 letters and 300-400 requests for tapes
and transcripts each time.
MONEY BOX (BBC Radio 4). This long running personal finance programme -
audience 750,000 - has a clearly established remit to provide independent
advice about savings, investment, tax and benefits.
It approaches from the consumer's point of view so expect tough but fair
questioning if your charges or products are under fire from customers. Most
straight interviews last two to three minutes.
WORLD BUSINESS REPORT (BBC World Service Radio). The audience is motley but
massive (120m). Popular in those parts of the developing world where
domestic broadcasting is state-controlled or newspapers are slow to arrive.
This is a fast-moving 24-hour operation pumping out three ten-minute
programmes of business and market news plus shorter bulletins in the main
World Service News Programmes. The World Service is justifiably renowned for
impartiality and accuracy.
THE NAMES AND THEIR COMPANIES (LBC). Chairmen or chief executives (no junior
ranks) can expect an unrivalled opportunity to talk at length (15-18
minutes) about their company in relaxed fashion, but to a relatively small
audience (30,000-35,000).
SKY NEWS. Most of its business slots last between three and six minutes.
Interviewees' clips generally last 15-20 seconds, although economists and
analysts can expect up to 2 1/2 minutes to foreshadow the day. Most
interviews are on location.
WORLD BUSINESS REPORT. (BBC World Service TV). A 26-minute flagship
programme, claiming the most comprehensive global audience, including
President Yeltsin's economic adviser. Produced by the team which puts out
BBC Business Breakfast, the approach is similar although the perspective is
more international.
EUROPEAN BUSINESS TODAY, FT REPORTS, WEST OF MOSCOW (all FTTV). All three
are unashamedly international with a European flavour. They are interested
only in big multinationals, especially the leading European players. There
is less original shooting and heavier reliance on relatively long
interviews.
WORLD BUSINESS TODAY (CNN International). Two pacey half-hour roundups of
the financial market from a US perspective. Claims one in three European
business executives watch at least once a week.
The author is a former programme editor on Channel 4's Business Daily
programme. He now heads the London-based media training consultancy Studio
Strategy.
