<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Management: Doctrines to salve corporate souls - Tim Dickson
considers the Christian view of modern business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Commercial interest in one of the most important Christian festivals reaches
fever pitch this week. But turning the spotlight the other way, what about
the Christian view of modern business?
This issue was addressed last month in a lecture to the Christian
Association of Business Executives by the Reverend Jack Mahoney, professor
of business ethics and corporate responsibility at the London Business
School.
Mahoney argued that Christian beliefs underpin a variety of attitudes, but
that giving 'due weight' to all of them permits encouragement for what
business is capable of doing, tempered by criticism and impatience for what
it is not doing, or doing to an insufficient degree. He outlined several
ways - among them ethical shopping and whistle-blowing - in which Christians
can promote business conduct in accordance with their values and principles.
To a large extent, Mahoney explained, Christian attitudes reflect the
emphasis individuals put on the four leading doctrines of Creation, Sin,
Salvation and Completion.
Traditional beliefs about death, judgment, heaven and hell, for example,
have often turned people's attention to the future and to the way in which
God will bring human history to 'completion'. This has led some Christians
to regard with suspicion, or at least moral reserve, all secular or worldly
activities, including business and the enterprise of wealth creation.
Completion admittedly took on a more dynamic expression with the development
of Christian political theology in the 1950s, partly in dialogue with
post-war Marxism. Hope, as Mahoney put it, 'was no longer a sedative or
spiritual aspirin' but a prescription for working to enable all people to
live lives worthy of their destiny. Liberation theology was just one of
several social and religious movements to find inspiration in this approach,
betraying not so much hostility towards business as such as indignation at
the unrelieved plight of the world's poor.
Sin is seen by many Christians as the outstanding characteristic of society,
with life viewed as a series of spiritual pitfalls - nowhere more evident
than in the world of business. Mahoney, however, rejects this absolutist
view, suggesting that the denunciation of consumerism may 'conceal a deeper
suspicion of material creation which at times verges on the heretical in
Christian terms'. He says New Testament warnings against individual
accretion of wealth should be put in the context of early Christians' lack
of interest in social ethics. The Gospel, he adds, has nothing to say about
the spiritual and moral dangers arising from poverty.
It is the doctrines of Creation and Salvation, though, which Mahoney says
most effectively counter the stress put on the role of business as social
villain and exploiter. The theology of the former shows that 'wealth and
riches should not be considered demonic or evil, but as having a positive
and God-given social purpose in the continuing work of advancing human
society'. Salvation contributes 'a note of Christian optimism . . . a belief
that even given the influence of sin there remains a radical goodness about
creation'.
Turning to ethics, Mahoney examined the responsibility of the three big
stakeholders in business: customers, investors and workers. While not
aligning himself formally with the 'vigilante' consumer movement in the US,
he nevertheless stated that the 'socially responsible use' of personal or
family resources was a 'Christian way of using one's economic purchasing
power to influence markets and guide business'.
He said shareholders should see themselves as 'trustees of an organic
ongoing enterprise rather than simply as the absolute possessors of inert
property'.
Mahoney also urged labour to mobilise its influence and power on behalf of
other stakeholders. Whistle-blowing may popularly be equated with
disloyalty, but 'it expresses a wider loyalty to society'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
