<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Break-up of British Gas ruled out: DTI rejects two main
recommendations of Monopolies Commission report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The decision on British Gas yesterday by Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and
industry secretary, means that he has rejected the two main recommendations
of August's Monopolies and Mergers Commission report - the first time he has
gone against the MMC in a significant inquiry.
He commended the commission on the 'high quality' of its reports, but made
it clear he disagreed with its analysis of the priorities in dealing with
the problem of British Gas's monopoly. He also felt a break-up of the
company was impractical and unnecessary.
Instead, he is proposing British Gas should have separate internal
businesses to overcome the conflict between its dual role as transporter and
trader of gas.
The MMC had said that true competition could never develop as long as
British Gas wielded such power over the market.
Mr Heseltine said: 'My view is that complete separation of the two
businesses within continued British Gas ownership is likely to be sufficient
to overcome the obstacle to competition which the MMC identified. I have
therefore decided not to require divestment.'
He was prepared, he said, to see how the restructuring on which British Gas
had already embarked would work. If it was unsatisfactory it would be up to
Ms Clare Spottiswoode, the gas regulator, to take appropriate action.
What seems to have tipped the balance against break-up is the speed with
which British Gas has changed since the MMC inquiry was launched more than a
year ago. As one person close to the decision said yesterday, the inquiry
was like 'a giant consultancy exercise' which forced British Gas to confront
tough issues and push through reforms in management and structure.
On the abolition of the monopoly, Mr Heseltine said he wanted a faster
timetable than that proposed by the MMC because of the government's strong
commitment to improving competition in gas supply. 'I am keen to make
further progress in reducing the monopoly as rapidly as possible. I do not
believe that the removal of the monopoly needs to be delayed as the MMC
envisaged.'
Ministers also wanted to get the gas market opened up at the same time as
electricity - in 1998. But a key point was that while independent companies
should be admitted to the franchise market, constraints on British Gas's
operations in the non-franchise market should also be removed.
