<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Price Waterhouse wins deferment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Price Waterhouse, the former BCCI auditors, yesterday won a deferment,
probably into the next century, of a disciplinary inquiry by the Institute
of Chartered Accountants into its role in the bank's collapse, John Mason
writes.
Three Court of Appeal judges ruled unanimously that to allow the inquiry to
proceed while civil litigation against the firm by BCCI's liquidators was
continuing could cause substantial prejudice.
The court granted an order quashing a decision by Sir John Bailey, the
inquiry chairman, for the ICA's investigation to start immediately. It ruled
that the inquiry could not start until the end of the civil litigation. This
is not likely before 2000.
The liquidators are claiming damages for negligence in connection with the
1985, 1986 and 1987 audits. The claim in regard to the 1985 audit is for
more than Dollars 8bn (Pounds 5.3bn).
Lord Justice Nolan said there was no urgency since there were no allegations
of misconduct and no questions about the firm's fitness to remain registered
auditors.
</TEXT>
