<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Abandoned pits pour out a toxic threat: After British Coal,
it is unclear who will be responsible for preventing minewater pollution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Rivers Authority, the river pollution watchdog, has warned the
government that it has inadequate powers to deal with pollution caused by
water from abandoned mines. Such water is a growing threat as British Coal
rapidly contracts.
The rundown of deep mining and British Coal's forthcoming privatisation has
thrown into doubt the future of its costly minewater pumping operations,
currently paid for by the corporation to protect working pits.
Without constant pumping, minewater in coalfield areas can rise into disused
workings and become contaminated with metals before leaching out into
rivers, killing wildlife and contaminating drinking water.
In County Durham, now without a single operating deep mine, studies have
suggested that discharges of polluted minewater into the River Wear would
begin three months after British Coal's Pounds 6m-a-year County Durham
pumping programme ceased.
The NRA, which has mounted no prosecutions over pollution by water from
abandoned mines since its formation in 1989, says the law hampers it from
taking action in such cases.
It says the problem is the 1991 Water Resources Act which states that
'permitting' water from an abandoned mine to enter controlled waters is not
an offence, although 'causing' it to do so is. Also, under the act the NRA
is not allowed to recoup the cost of clearing up after such incidents.
NRA chief scientist Mr Jan Pentreath says the law in this area is deficient
and must be altered. 'The NRA has said this publicly again and again.'
The NRA's plea for stronger powers comes as MPs, environmentalists and
industry - including the water industry - together with rural interests,
including the National Farmers' Union, are increasingly expressing concern
about potential minewater pollution.
Nobody knows precisely how great the threat is. British Coal's present
pumping regime has, until now, helped to prevent pollution from
long-abandoned workings. But a 1991 incident in which 80m gallons of water
contaminated with toxic metals spewed out of the Wheal Jane tin mine in
Cornwall, turning the River Carnon red and endangering marine life,
illustrated minewater's hidden power.
In its coal privatisation bill, the government proposes that a new
public-sector body, the Coal Authority, take over British Coal's
responsibilities for the physical legacy of historical mining not
transferred to the private sector.
The 160-page bill sets out a framework for licensing of mining, safety,
pensions, concessionary fuel, coal-bed methane exploitation and subsidence,
but does not mention minewater pollution or pumping. 'This kind of detail is
worked out during the passage of the bill,' the Department of Trade and
Industry said.
Mr Tim Eggar, energy minister, last week said the NRA's complaint that the
law is deficient was a Department of the Environment matter.
County Durham Labour MPs and councillors have met Mr Eggar to express
disquiet. Conservative MPs in mining areas, such as Mr Richard Alexander, MP
for Newark, Nottinghamshire, are also worried.
'British Coal is apparently overlooking the likelihood of their underground
water, which may be contaminated with metals, leaching into the rest of the
water and consequently the water supply,' he says. With other MPs he has
lobbied Mr John Gummer, environment secretary. 'Clearly the state has a
responsibility,' says Mr Alexander.
Mr Howard Gill, regional operations adviser at Northumbrian Water's sewage
and water arm, says: 'These discharges are a direct result of the closure of
an industry; the costs should be recognised as part of that closure
programme. They shouldn't fall on water consumers in a few years' time.'
There were suspicions, he adds, that the 1991 act was phrased so as not to
saddle companies with long-term minewater pollution responsibilities. There
is evidence of the deterrent effect of pumping costs - RJB Mining dropped
its bid for Easington pit in County Durham for this reason.
Mr Gill says the water industry fears that hard-won improvements in river
quality may be lost. North East Water has warned that if pumping ceases,
possible minewater pollution in the River Wear could force it to spend
Pounds 25m on new treatment facilities.
Minewater pumping is also sometimes useful to water companies in maintaining
environmental standards. The Clean Rivers Trust, a Nottinghamshire-based
environmental group committed to working with industry, says that without
regular inflows of pumped minewater some stretches of rivers in its area
would consist mainly of treated sewage.
Mr Harvey Wood, trust co-ordinator, says minewater has implications
nationally for many industries, including agriculture, tourism and brewing.
'I don't think it's being taken seriously at the moment,' he says.
Minewater, he adds, is unpredictable. 'It has a very nasty habit of popping
up where it's least expected.'
One man who knows this to his cost is farmer Mr Peter Raine. In 1979 a
concrete plug on a disused pit shaft near his farm at St Helen Auckland, an
area of County Durham once extensively mined, was blown off by the pressure
of underground water. Since then his field drainage ditches have begun
overflowing with water, turning 10 acres into bogland. It is land where once
he grew winter barley, grazed cattle and made hay. Now it squelches, sodden
and useless, over the top of his gumboots.
Mr Raine is certain the water has risen through abandoned mineworkings. His
worries were heightened by the death of five cattle from poisoning several
years ago. Fearing contamination, he has zoned off a further 10 acres of
grazing land.
Yet, in spite of the anxiety and lost income, he has found no means of
redress and no way of stopping the flow of water. 'How do I prove it's
coming from a pit shaft?' he asks. 'And who's going to take responsibility
for the problem, especially after British Coal's privatisation?'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Coal Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9511 Air, Water, and Solid Waste Management.
</IN>
