<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Whitehall clash on Post Office rules: DTI defies Treasury
over commercial freedom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Trade and Industry is backing the Post Office's call for
more commercial freedom, in spite of Treasury opposition.
DTI officials are working on a report contrasting the position of hospital
trusts and grant-maintained schools with that of the Post Office. They feel
that under the present rules some schools and hospital trusts have more
opportunities than the Post Office to involve the private sector.
The DTI wants to relax restrictions which prevent the Post Office from
forming international joint ventures to compete with the Dutch post office,
which is being privatised early next year.
The Treasury opposes any change to the status quo while the Post Office
remains in the public sector. According to Whitehall officials, the Treasury
is adamant that unless the Post Office is privatised, the corporation should
'not be entitled to any commercial freedom whatsoever'.
The two departments are so far apart on the issue that Mr Michael Portillo,
chief secretary to the Treasury, has blocked a move by Mr Michael Heseltine,
trade and industry secretary, to allow post offices to sell angling
licences, currently available from angling shops.
Treasury ministers do not believe post offices should have more scope to
compete with shops while the corporation remains state-owned. The DTI has
yet to announce the outcome of its long-awaited review of the Post Office.
An early draft of the report, not expected to be published until the end of
February, has come out against full privatisation but is known to be
sympathetic to the Post Office's call for greater freedom.
Mr Patrick McLoughlin, DTI minister responsible for the Post Office, is also
understood to be strongly supportive of its demand to be allowed to sign
international joint ventures with private companies.
Mr Mike Heron, Post Office chairman, and Mr Bill Cockburn, its chief
executive, fear that its investment plans and profitability are at risk
because of the cash taken by the Treasury.
The Post Office's external finance limit target - the amount it has to pay
the government - has risen to Pounds 230m in 1994-95 and is set at Pounds
210m for the following year.
It was announced yesterday that Post Office pre-tax profits fell from Pounds
135m to Pounds 59m in the six months to September, reflecting the impact of
the two-year freeze on letter prices.
Mr Cockburn has warned that in the long term, stamp prices may have to rise
to meet the Treasury's demands for cash. He said yesterday the Post Office
should be freed from the commercial constraint of helping to finance the
public sector borrowing requirement.
</TEXT>
