<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Birmingham Tories urge land deals to aid schools
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Derelict or under-used public land should be made available at no charge to
construction companies if, in exchange, they repair and refurbish rundown
schools, Birmingham Conservative councillors suggested yesterday.
Mr Bernard Zissmann, leader of the Conservative group on Birmingham city
council, advanced the idea to put pressure on the Labour-led council and to
offer 'a new dimension in tackling a national problem'.
The city council has been told by a commission of advisers of its own choice
that it has been under-spending on education. The commission noted that over
the past five years the council has pushed money into projects such as the
International Convention Centre but spent Pounds 236m less on education than
the government thought it should have done.
The advisers called for a Pounds 250m five-year programme to repair the
city's schools.
Mr Zissmann said: 'I don't think the city council will ever commit enough
money, not because it doesn't want to, but because it hasn't got the money.'
He said the Conservative suggestion would improve the infrastructure without
increasing the public sector borrowing requirement. Derelict land would also
be developed and the public stock of land reduced, in line with government
wishes.
Under Mr Zissmann's plan, a school needing repair would be identified and a
nearby vacant site located. A tender among construction companies would be
held and the land provided with outline planning permission as a quid pro
quo for the refurbishment of the school.
The council dismissed the scheme as one of 'Heath Robinson complexity which
will only increase red tape and bureaucracy'. All the council wanted, it
said, was an increase in its borrowing limits so that it could have the same
kind of rolling programme for school repairs enjoyed by the shire counties.
'The idea has the smell of a pre-election gimmick,' the council said. The
Conservatives need to gain four seats at next May's elections to take
control of the city - the UK's largest metropolitan authority - for the
first time in 10 years.
The land-for-school-repair scheme is, said Mr Zissmann, 'the main plank of
our election platform. If we can't get education right, there's not much
point in bothering about anything else'.
</TEXT>
