<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Ailing shipyard wins EU lifeline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Swan Hunter, the Tyneside shipbuilder in receivership, yesterday won
eligibility for Shipbuilding Intervention Funding subsidy which will be paid
by the UK government.
The decision, taken by European commissioners in Brussels, improves the
company's prospects of finding a buyer by enhancing its competitiveness in
bidding for merchant ship orders.
But restrictions placed on fund eligibility mean that the concession,
although a political triumph, only offers a breathing space while the
company tries to secure its future.
The company's eligibility for the 9 per cent subsidy is limited to a maximum
of Pounds 7m for a two-year period, and will be applied to no more than two
to three merchant orders. The European Commission described the conversion
back to a merchant yard as 'partial and limited'.
Factors behind the Commission's decision included the UK government's
commitment that this was a 'one-off' request which did not set a precedent
for other military yards, the limited effect on the EU's production capacity
and the effect eligibility would have in increasing the receivers' chances
of finding a purchaser for the yard.
The decision was warmly welcomed by unions, local MPs and MEPs, local
authorities and industry minister Mr Tim Sainsbury. Swan Hunter, he said,
played a vital role in the UK's ability to maintain its naval defence
capability.
Mr Ed James of Price Waterhouse, the receivers which are running the company
and are seeking to sell it as a going concern, said the news must increase
its attractiveness to prospective purchasers. 'We hope that it will
encourage them to develop an interest in what is a lean, fit and
increasingly competitive yard.'
Mr Steve Byers, Wallsend Labour MP, said yesterday: 'A prospective buyer can
now see the whole picture. We are now waiting in the next six weeks for a
buyer to come forward. If that doesn't happen, I think we have seen the end
of shipbuilding on the Tyne.'
</TEXT>
