<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Treasury reshuffle targets efficiency: Changes signal intent
to focus on wealth creation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Treasury has launched its most sweeping reorganisation for a decade in a
bid to improve management efficiency and counter criticism that it is out of
touch with the business world.
The moves, announced yesterday, will give more responsibilities to
relatively junior officials and set up a new directorate to handle policies
affecting industry, including education and employment.
Sir Terry Burns, Treasury permanent secretary, will link more closely with
officials lower down the department who will report directly to him.
The shift, to take effect next month, is intended to make the Treasury more
receptive to events outside Whitehall.
It is the strongest signal yet from the government's most powerful
department that it intends to change its culture to focus more on wealth
creation.
The changes come after criticism from industrialists and non-government
economists in recent years that the Treasury has developed too few contacts
with the business world and has been slow to react to outside events.
In particular, critics have said the department failed to wake up early
enough to the seriousness of the recession, and also to sense the pressures
on sterling prior to Britain's departure from the European exchange rate
mechanism 15 months ago.
Sir Terry has spent the past 18 months refining ways to reform the
Treasury's management.
He has recently been working with Ms Wendy Pritchard, a management
consultant, on ways to alter the department's culture.
The biggest element of the change is the regrouping of the Treasury's
financial services and industry divisions into one directorate under Mr
Steve Robson, a high-flying Treasury official currently in charge of
industry policies.
Mr Robson will take charge of the Treasury's responsibilities for
supervising financial institutions, and also for policies to help industry
work more effectively. Such 'supply side' policies include ways to attract
more private-sector involvement into large projects normally funded by the
government.
On the same deputy-secretary level as Mr Robson will be three other
officials who cover civil-service pay and management, public services, and
fiscal and monetary policy.
As part of the reshuffle, two of the Treasury's current deputy secretaries -
Ms Rachel Lomax, in charge of financial institutions, and Mr Huw Evans,
number two to Sir Nigel Wicks in overseas affairs - are moving to new jobs
and are not being replaced.
Ms Lomax is to become economic adviser at the Cabinet Office while Mr Evans
is to become the UK's representative at the International Monetary Fund and
the World Bank.
Mr Brian Fox is moving to the Cabinet Office from his current Treasury job
as head of establishments and organisation.
</TEXT>
