<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Indian MPs savage the financial establishment: The Bombay
stocks scandal inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rarely can a parliamentary inquiry into a financial scandal have produced
such a comprehensively damning report as that published yesterday by Indian
MPs examining last year's Rs40bn (Pounds 850m) Bombay stock market scandal.
The committee criticised almost every aspect of India's financial markets -
its banks, brokers, leasing companies, industrial groups, state-owned
industry, the Reserve Bank of India and the government. It catalogued
hundreds of sins of commission and omission in language bordering on the
Biblical and called for punishment with a withering disregard of extenuating
circumstances. As one Indian newspaper editor said last night: 'It's full of
simulated moral outrage.' The scandal involved the illegal siphoning of
funds from banks to the stock market through the collusion of bankers,
brokers, and public and private sector companies. MPs pull their punches in
respect of only two people - Mr P V Narasimha Rao, the prime minister, and
Mr Manmohan Singh, the finance minister. In Mr Narasimha Rao's case they
refrain from commenting on the explosive allegations made this summer by Mr
Harshad Mehta, the broker at the centre of the scandal, that he tried to
bribe the prime minister with a suitcase full of money.
In Mr Manmohan Singh's case, the committee avoids holding him responsible by
name for his ministry's alleged failings - though the report does say in
scarcely veiled language that 'the responsibility and accountability of the
minister of finance to parliament cannot be denied.'
Mr Narasimha Rao and Mr Manmohan Singh escaped because of their political
importance. Opposition members of the committee said yesterday they would
have pursued both ministers more vigorously given the chance.
The ruling Congress (I) party's success in keeping Mr Narasimha Rao and Mr
Manmohan Singh's names off the list of the guilty indicates that the
political impact of the report may be limited.
Nevertheless the committee was fiercely critical of virtually everyone
concerned:
Mr Manmohan Singh's plea that a distinction be drawn between his direct
responsibilities and those of the ministry and institutions he oversees was
rejected. 'Such a distinction cannot be sustained by the constitutional
jurisprudence under which the parliamentary system works.'
The finance ministry failed to anticipate the scandal, to respond to it
properly, to manage the effects, to apply the necessary post-scandal reforms
and to punish the guilty resolutely. Among other shortcomings, the committee
found that the ministry's representative attended only 15 of 49 meetings of
the Reserve Bank of India's central board in 1986-92. MPs say this was
negligent.
The Reserve Bank of India (the central bank) was accused of ignoring warning
signs as far back as 1986; of not following up the findings of inspection
reports; of turning a blind eye to irregularities and of being soft on
foreign banks for fear of upsetting India's international creditworthiness.
Three present or former senior officials are accused by name of 'gross
dereliction of duty.' MPs recommended establishing a Board of Financial
Supervision inside the central bank to assume from the main board overall
responsibility for banking supervision.
Banks were accused of management failings, including lax checks on
transactions and book-keeping. The finance ministry was accused of being
negligent in its role of appointing the senior director of the many
state-owned banks. MPs recommended reform of the recruitment procedures to
bring in candidates from outside the civil service.
Foreign banks were blamed for originating the scandal and becoming the
biggest players in it, and for throwing overboard 'all principles of
prudence and safety.' Standard Chartered Bank, ANZ Grindlays, Citibank and
Bank of America, the main operators in the inter-bank securities market
among foreign banks, were singled out for particular attack for allegedly
breaking Indian laws and infringing laws in their own countries.
Public Sector Units were criticised for allowing their funds, mostly secured
via cheap government-backed credits, to be recycled into stock market
investments. 'All this was public money and all who were playing with it
were public servants.'
The Bombay Stock Exchange was second only to the foreign banks as a target
for the committee's venom. Insider trading by brokers, reluctance to publish
price data openly, ineffective audits and tax returns and virtually
non-existent punitive action on the part of the stock exchange authorities
were all highlighted.
The committee urged the finance ministry to crack down quickly and heavily
on individuals involved in the scandal and still occupying senior positions
in banks, brokers and elsewhere. The banking laws should be strengthened to
include harsher penalties for wrong-doing. Stringent penalties should be
imposed on foreign banks 'including suspension of their licences'.
MPs accepted that the creation of the Securities and Exchange Board of
India, the markets watchdog which started operating after the scandal, would
improve regulation. But they said it had come too late and needed to be
tough.
The committee wrongly linked the scandal to the economic liberalisation
which started in mid-1991.
In fact, the origins of the affair pre-date reform and its causes lie in the
complex mix of restrictive regulations and ineffective supervision which
characterised the pre-reform financial system.
MPs urged the government to give full weight to improving supervision saying
'deregulation without effective checks and balances would be an unmitigated
disaster.'
</TEXT>
