<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Israel and Palestinians edging towards compromise on borders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Israel and the Palestine Liberation Organisation appeared to be edging
towards a compromise in deadlocked peace negotiations as the two sides
resumed top-level talks in Paris last night.
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, Israel's prime minister, said his government would accept
Palestinian co-ordination at border crossings 'as long as we will be able to
control, for the sake of security, everybody that crosses'.
In Tunis, PLO officials indicated that Mr Yassir Arafat, PLO chairman, had
agreed to back down on his demand for full Palestinian control of border
crossings between Egypt and the Gaza Strip and the West Bank area of Jericho
and Jordan.
The officials said the PLO was prepared to concede control in return for
extensive powers for Palestinian police at checkpoints.
The issue of border control has been the main point impeding the
Israeli-Palestinian peace accord's implementation.
Israel has insisted the peace deal left external security exclusively in the
hands of the Jewish state and has accused Mr Arafat of trying to win
important concessions over sovereignty, which the agreement left to later
negotiations.
Mr Rabin told the foreign affairs and defence committee of Israel's
parliament yesterday that the US, European Union, Egypt and Morocco
supported Israel's interpretation of the peace accord as did Mr Mahmoud
Abbas, the PLO official who signed the agreement with Israel in September.
Israeli officials said the inclusion of Mr Abbas in the Palestinian team
meeting Mr Shimon Peres, Israeli foreign minister, in Paris last night was a
sign of progress.
Mr Abbas has reportedly been at loggerheads with Mr Arafat for several weeks
over the PLO chairman's management of peace talks.
Officials said that once a compromise was found on the border issue,
resolution of the other key obstacle - the size of the Jericho area - would
be relatively quick.
Meanwhile, in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, Gulf Arab states yesterday discussed the
possibility of easing the Arab economic boycott of Israel. Mr Youssef Bin
Alawi Bin Abdullah, Omani foreign minister of state, said: 'Lifting the
boycott could be in our favour.' Diplomats, however, said it was unlikely
the Gulf states would lift the boycott before there was a united Arab
decision through the Arab League.
</TEXT>
