<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / US telecoms controls face overhaul: Clinton administration
aims to ease competition rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Clinton administration aims to introduce legislation next month
overhauling the tight controls on competition in the telecommunications and
information industries.
Faced with advancing technologies that have blurred the traditional lines
between sectors such as local and long distance telephone, or cable and
broadcast television, the administration plans to rewrite the 1934
Communications Act that still provides the framework for most of the rules
governing telecommunications.
The new legislation would also ease restrictions imposed by the 1982 court
judgment that broke up the AT&amp;T telephone monopoly into a group of 'Baby
Bells' providing local telephone service and a separate AT&amp;T offering long
distance service.
Vice-President Al Gore yesterday outlined the administration's ideas on
telecommunications reform, and was expected to give greater detail at a
speech in Los Angeles on January 11.
Mr Gore's aim is to establish new regulatory models that will take
technological changes into account and pave the way for much more open
competition in all sectors.
'The desired end point is to move to a point ultimately where any company
can offer any services through any network to any set of consumers,' an
administration official said.
The administration is expected to draw heavily on separate bills that have
already been introduced in Congress. One Senate bill would allow the Bell
companies to offer cable television, while also requiring all telephone
service providers to open their networks to rivals, and guaranteeing
universal local telephone access.
Separate bills in the House would progressively ease the ban on Bell
companies making telecommunications equipment or offering long distance
service and allow telephone and cable companies to compete in each other's
markets.
Officials say that developments such as cellular telephone networks and
fibre optic television links have made it possible to have full competition
in every segment of the telecommunications business, so that the rigid rules
designed to prevent abuse of the local telephone monopoly were no longer as
necessary.
'Everything we do now through wires in the ground we are going to do in the
air, and everything we do now in the air we are going to do through wires in
the ground,' an administration official said.
Some of this blurring of lines is already in progress with moves such as
AT&amp;T's Dollars 12.3bn deal to buy McCaw Cellular Communications, the largest
US cellphone operator, or the proposed Dollars 22bn takeover of
Tele-Communications Inc, the largest cable television company, by Bell
Atlantic, one of the Baby Bells.
</TEXT>
