<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Japan's bureaucrats find their citadel under siege
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's bureaucrats, who believe they have run the country successfully for
more than four decades, are suddenly under attack from a new coalition
government that wants to weaken their grip on power.
A dispute has arisen between Mr Hiroshi Kumagai, minister for international
trade and industry, and his ministry, which likes to think it guided
Japanese industry's remarkable rise from the wartime ashes.
Mr Kumagai has demanded the resignation of one of the ministry's most senior
officials, Mr Masahisa Naito, who is alleged to have unusually close ties to
some companies and to have promoted unfairly another bureaucrat just before
he left the ministry to stand as a candidate for the Liberal Democratic
party.
'Enforcement of official discipline at administrative bodies is a big
challenge for the government,' Mr Kumagai said. 'We have to correct these
practices.'
The issue of appointments is particularly sensitive for bureaucrats, who
have traditionally arranged their own promotion ladder and sought soft
landings in industry after retiring from the ministry. While claiming to be
non-political, senior bureaucrats have often looked ahead to a second career
as a politician, generally with the LDP.
Mr Naito, director-general of the industrial policy bureau, denies having
unusually close ties to industry and argues he should not resign for
continuing the tradition of promoting a fellow bureaucrat leaving to become
a politician. The idea is that a promotion, if in name only, would improve
the candidate's chances of election, though it would also give an enduring
sense of obligation to the ministry.
Behind the row is an attempt by Mr Kumagai, a former Miti man himself, to
strengthen the control of the Japan Renewal party over a bureaucracy
sympathetic to the LDP. Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, the leader of a
separate party, said he would let the minister solve the dispute, while LDP
officials complained that the case was an 'unprecedented political intrusion
into the bureaucracy'.
Mr Hosokawa had promised to reduce the influence of Tokyo bureaucrats, but
his inexperienced government has been accused of being even more dependent
on them than the LDP. However, the government is attempting to cut
bureaucratic collusion in awarding construction contracts and to reduce
powers through deregulation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
