<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Leading index falls again: Jobs at risk as companies review
workforce needs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's economy is weakening because of faltering consumer demand and a drop
in capital spending, the Economic Planning Agency said yesterday after its
leading economic index showed another fall for the month of October.
The index slipped from 33.3 per cent in September to 30 per cent. The EPA
regards any reading lower than 50 per cent as an indication of weakness.
In August the index had risen to 50 per cent, inspiring government hopes of
a recovery, but economic activity has since slowed and the coalition
government is under pressure to introduce a new stimulative package.
Meanwhile, the Bank of Japan said yesterday that no clear signs of recovery
had emerged, and companies were reviewing their workforce needs, which could
lead to a rise in unemployment.
In its report for December, the bank agreed with the EPA that declining
personal consumption and capital spending were holding back the economy,
although slow lending growth by banks is attributed more to weak corporate
demand than to the wariness of banks.
Business leaders have called for another cut in the official discount rate,
but bank officials said yesterday they were still studying the effects of
the most recent reduction, in September, when the rate was cut to 1.75 per
cent.
</TEXT>
