<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Belgian socialists may be probed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Belgium's French-speaking socialists are bracing themselves for a troubled
new year, after a magistrate asked for parliamentary immunity of three
socialist ministers to be lifted so she could pursue her investigation into
a political scandal.
Mrs Veronique Ancia, an investigating magistrate from Liege, is following up
allegations that francophone socialists were bribed to award a 1988 contract
for military helicopters to Agusta, the Italian aircraft manufacturer.
On Monday, she asked the Belgian parliament and the assemblies of the
Walloon region and French-speaking community to lift the immunity of Mr Guy
Coeme, Belgian communications minister, Mr Guy Spitaels, minister-president
of Wallonia, and Mr Guy Mathot, Walloon minister of internal affairs.
The request - which should be answered by the end of January - was not
unexpected. But it could herald a new phase in the complex inquiry, which
has been hampered by lack of resources. Parliament officials said the case
did not imply that the trio were under suspicion themselves. The officials
said if immunity was not lifted, the Liege authorities would be restricted
in use of evidence supplied by the ministers.
Mrs Ancia's inquiries have already taken her to Italy, where she questioned
Mr Bettino Craxi, former Italian socialist leader. She also spoke to Mr
Roberto d'Alessandro, chairman of Agusta, who was imprisoned earlier this
year in connection with separate bribery allegations. Mrs Ancia is also
examining links with the unsolved murder in 1991 of Mr Andre Cools, a
prominent Liege socialist politician.
The ministers will only be asked about the Agusta dossier. At the time, Mr
Coeme was Belgium's defence minister, and Mr Spitaels was head of the
French-speaking socialist party. Mr Mathot was described in a 1988 fax sent
from Agusta Belgium to the company's headquarters in Italy as 'one of the
levers' in award of the contract.
Mr Spitaels said on Monday he and senior party officials were not involved
in the Agusta decision. Mr Mathot has also denied involvement. Mr Coeme
claims 'not one centime' was incorrectly spent on the helicopter deal.
The Agusta contract was for 46 helicopters, the last of which should be
delivered to the Belgian army next month. Agusta has repeatedly declared it
was 'completely unconnected with any financial dealings directly or
indirectly aimed at illegal purposes'.
</TEXT>
