<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Commission wants equal tax treatment in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission yesterday heralded a new approach to tax
harmonisation by adopting a recommendation aimed at ending discrimination
against non-resident taxpayers.
The Commission is calling on member states to grant the same tax benefits to
200,000-300,000 EU citizens working beyond the borders of their home country
as they currently do to residents. Many cross-border workers are unable to
claim family and married couple tax allowances at home or abroad.
The Commission has asked governments to bring national legislation and
bilateral tax agreements with other EU members into line with the
recommendation by 1995. If national rules are not harmonised, a formal
directive could be proposed. Brussels will continue to pursue governments
through the European Court of Justice, using the recommendation as a basis
for complaints.
Senior Commission officials said yesterday the approach was one way of
unblocking proposals on tax, which require unanimous approval from member
states. Such measures are often opposed by governments which fear losing
revenue and sovereignty over tax matters. A broad recommendation could be
used, for example, to speed harmonisation of tax treatment for small and
medium-sized companies.
</TEXT>
