<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Brussels clears aid for Aer Lingus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission yesterday authorised a IPounds 175m (Pounds 168m)
equity injection by the Irish government into Aer Lingus, its troubled state
airline, as part of a big restructuring package to return it to commercial
viability.
However, the Commission has attached strict conditions over the use of the
aid 'to avoid any effects which could be contrary to the common interest'.
These include:
Aer Lingus must not expand its operating fleet during the two-year
restructuring plan.
Aer Lingus' European operations, transatlantic operations and a proposed
'low-cost, no-frills' operation known as Aer Lingus Express - planned for
the Dublin-London route - will be operated as separate legal entities with
separate accounts.
Aer Lingus Express must only use existing aircraft in its fleet if
established during the restructuring period.
No additional seating capacity will be placed on its Ireland-UK routes
during the restructuring programme.
The equity is to be used only for restructuring and not for acquiring
shareholdings in any Community carrier.
No further grant aid is to be given to Aer Lingus.
Sir Michael Bishop, the chairman of British Midland, Aer Lingus' main
competitor on the busy Dublin-Heathrow route, yesterday welcomed 'the strong
and meaningful conditions imposed by the Commission' and called it a
'landmark decision in staunching the unconditional flow of money into
loss-making European state-owned airlines by national governments'. But he
warned that if it transpires that the aid is used other than solely for
restructuring 'we will consider legal action'.
He said that concerns expressed by Aer Lingus' competitors over the danger
of cross-subsidising of 'uneconomic fares' by Aer Lingus on the
Dublin-London route 'appears to have been ignored by today's ruling'.
Aer Lingus, which has debts of IPounds 550m, yesterday welcomed the
Commission decision. It said the restrictions on the aid would affect its
ability to compete and that it expected to return to 'modest profitability'
in 1994-95.
The equity is to be paid in three tranches. The first of IPounds 75m will be
made before the end of the year; IPounds 56m of this is to be used to
finance redundancies, the remainder to reduce debt. The two other tranches
of IPounds 50m each will also be used for debt reduction and will be made in
1994 and 1995.
</TEXT>
