<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Walesa tells how to handle Zhirinovsky: Anthony Robinson and
Christopher Bobinski hear how the west should react to Russia's vote winner
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON and CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The people of Poland were shocked three years ago when a quarter of them
voted for an obscure Polish-Canadian called Stan Tyminski in the elections
which brought Lech Walesa to the presidential palace. Mr Vladimir
Zhirinovsky won a similar share in last week's Russian elections. But when
Poles voted again three months ago Stan Tyminski and his 'Party X' won less
than 5 per cent of votes and thus failed to gain any representation in the
new parliament.
Is Mr Zhirinovsky destined for a similar descent into obscurity? According
to President Walesa what happened in Russia was no surprise. 'I have said a
thousand times that events in the post-communist world follow a different
logic than to those in the west.'
Economic deprivation makes the electorate vulnerable to the sort of populist
'solutions' offered by people like Mr Tyminski and Mr Zhirinovsky. 'This is
a phase which the post-communist countries go through,' Mr Walesa said.
'It does not lead to a return to communism, but it does open the way for the
return to power of the 'activists' I mentioned earlier, people who will do
everything necessary, including turning their party cards from red to green,
in order to regain power.'
So does this mean that the market reformers should slow their pace? Mr
Walesa thinks not. 'In Poland's case, Leszek Balcerowicz (the architect of
Poland's shock therapy reforms) did a good job. A man like him is needed in
every post-communist country. But I said from the start that men like
Balcerowicz need a twin, a whole group of people, who come after him, to
pick up the pieces.'
Poles are acutely aware of the differences between their country, with its
Catholic faith and traditional western orientation, and Russia with its
imperial past, weak democratic traditions, huge size and ethnic complexity.
They recognise differences between the unknown, rootless Tyminski and the
better educated, better known and more deeply rooted Zhirinovsky with his
gut feel for the depth of Russian self-pity and resentment.
But, having been the pioneers of economic shock therapy only four years ago,
Poles empathise with the struggling citizens of Russia and other former
Soviet states. Polish economists in particular are aware that the really
painful stage of structural reform, involving mass redundancies and soaring
unemployment, has hardly even begun in Russia or in neighbouring Ukraine.
Asked how the west should react to the snapshot of Russia presented by the
election results, President Walesa returned to his view that the west had
failed to work out a constructive policy towards the former communist world
and remained hobbled by attitudes formed during the cold war.
Like his counterparts throughout central Europe and the Baltic states, Mr
Walesa argues that the former Soviet-controlled states of the region are
best equipped to become a channel of western support for continuing reform
in Russia. But he adds that the former Soviet satellite countries will only
be able to play such a role if they are securely integrated into hitherto
exclusively western structures like the European Union and Nato.
'In the old days when Europe was divided into hostile blocs it made sense
not to admit poorer, less-developed states who would perhaps weaken the
overall strength of the western bloc. But now that the Warsaw Pact has
disappeared this argument no longer applies and we should be admitted into
the European house even though we are poorer cousins,' he said.
'The top priority now is to stop Russia falling prey to anarchy and the most
effective way would be to channel assistance through countries like Poland.
We not only have recent experience of market reforms but also open borders
with the eastern countries. We offer the best and cheapest way of reducing
the security risks in this region and help strengthen Russia's reformers.'
This view is shared by many other leaders in the region who fear being left
in limbo between east and west. After the Russian elections their views will
not be so easy to ignore when Nato leaders meet in Brussels for their summit
early in the New Year with Mr Zhirinovsky's wilder threats of
re-incorporating Finland, the Baltic states and Poland still ringing in
their ears.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
    PLZ  Poland, East Europe.
</CN>
