<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Shipyards win aid extension
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission has extended the system for providing subsidies to
European Union shipbuilders for another year, and called on non-EU
governments to make greater efforts to cut anti-competitive practices before
the end of next year.
The Commission agreed to maintain production aid for new ships at 9 per cent
of the value of contracts after January 1 1994. Aid for ship conversions and
the building of small ships will be limited to 4.5 per cent.
The EU had hoped to eliminate all shipbuilding subsidies in the Union by the
end of this year, but it was decided in May that the deteriorating economic
position of EU shipbuilders made that politically impossible.
In a statement, the Commission said the EU was looking to end subsidies by
January 1 1995, but only if other parties eliminated all their trade
distorting measures and regulations such as injurious pricing, home credit
schemes and domestic-build requirements.
The Commission singled out the US, Japan and Korea for particular criticism,
and also attacked 'high aid levels' available in certain Efta countries.
Swan Hunter lifeline, Page 4
</TEXT>
