<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Candidates closer to EU entry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER and HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Talks to enlarge the European Union were given a boost yesterday when
Austria, Sweden, Finland and Norway agreed a formula to accommodate their
environmental, health and safety standards.
All four candidates also agreed they would fully support the foreign and
security policy of the Union. EU negotiators said alarm over the swing
towards the neo-fascists in the Russian elections had enhanced the desire of
the four to belong to a common European security framework. All except
Norway had previously been neutral countries.
Yesterday's breakthrough - described by the EU and candidate countries as 'a
Christmas present' - keeps alive hopes of concluding negotiations by March,
in order to get the four in by January 1995.
'We are very much encouraged by what we have done today,' said Mr Bjorn Tore
Godal, trade minister and chief negotiator for Norway, the most difficult
candidate for the EU to take in, because of a range of special demands on
fish, energy and agriculture.
But all four candidates had felt vulnerable before their electorates on the
environment, where the EU was seen as demanding lower standards in order to
remove impediments to trade.
In the event, EU negotiators came up with a three-pronged approach which on
the face of it looks as though the 12 are adjusting upwards to higher Nordic
and Alpine standards.
If standards are equivalent, even though different - for example on car
emissions - Brussels refused to budge. The candidates get transitional
exemptions where the EC has decided to raise standards, but not yet (for
instance on safety belts). Crucially, to deal with the most sensitive areas
such as health labelling on products and pesticides, the candidates will get
transitional exemptions with a review after four years, by when all four
said yesterday they expected to be inside the EU with a full vote.
Among other issues settled yesterday was a derogation to the Swedes on snus,
or oral moist snuff, regarded as a health hazard outside Sweden and Norway.
Mr Ulf Dinkelspiel, Sweden's minister for Europe, said it had 'saved my
Christmas'.
The accords received an enthusiastic welcome from Sweden's mainstream
parties, with the leadership of the opposition Social Democratic party
adding crucial support.
Opposition to Sweden's membership stands at near 50 per cent, with less than
30 per cent in favour. As a result, winning over opposition among supporters
of the Social Democrats, Sweden's biggest political party, is seen as vital
to securing a 'yes' to membership in a planned referendum.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ATZ  Austria, West Europe.
    SEZ  Sweden, West Europe.
    FIZ  Finland, West Europe.
    NOZ  Norway, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9511 Air, Water, and Solid Waste Management.
    P9229 Public Order and Safety, NEC.
</IN>
