<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Kravchuk confident of nuclear accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JILL BARSHAY and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Leonid Kravchuk claimed last night that an agreement had been
reached with the US and Russia to dismantle Ukraine's nuclear arms - but
Washington was more cautious, saying only that progress had been made.
Mr Kravchuk told reporters: 'We have already agreed with the US and Russia
that there will be a tripartite agreement on compensation, (security)
guarantees, technical and scientific aid.'
He said he and US Vice President Al Gore discussed the agreement during a
brief meeting in Budapest on Saturday. But the Ukrainian leader did not say
when such an agreement would be signed.
A Ukrainian government official said at the weekend there was preliminary
agreement with Russia and the US on the idea of compensation for Ukraine's
nuclear arsenal. Mr Kravchuk's reference to security guarantees and
dismantlement aid went much further.
The Ukrainian parliament, during its ratification of the Start-1 nuclear
arms reduction treaty last month, put three main conditions on relinquishing
all its 176 long-range missiles and 37 strategic bombers: uranium
compensation, dismantlement aid and security guarantees. Parliament has not
retreated from its conditions and at a session yesterday it questioned the
government's decision to take 17 nuclear missiles off military alert without
parliament's approval.
On Monday Ukraine announced that 20 of its 46 modern SS-24 missiles would be
deactivated by year's end. The rest could be taken off military alert by the
end of 1994. Ten of Ukraine's 130 SS-19s have already been dismantled.
Officials in Washington said that although significant progress had been
made in the talks between Ukraine, Russia and the US in recent days, Mr
Kravchuk's comments last night represented a wish list rather than an
agreement.
Mr Strobe Talbott, the State Department's special adviser on the former
Soviet Union, said that he was 'somewhat encouraged,' but that the talks so
far could not be described as reaching a final agreement.
'The two sides are moving closer together,' he said.
Ukraine has told Russian and US envoys that it wants a formal document
spelling out the compensation and security guarantees it will get in
exchange for giving up the nuclear weapons on its territory, but Russia
would like a less formal understanding.
While Russia believes its own security guarantee should be enough for
Ukraine, the Kiev government has asked the western nuclear powers for a
commitment, since it is reluctant to accept a guarantee from the nation it
views as the greatest threat to its security.
But the US is unlikely to agree to anything as binding as a treaty
commitment to defend Ukraine in the event of attack.
US officials have held out the carrot of financial aid, but they argue that
Ukraine must first dismantle the missiles on its territory, as it has
already promised to do, before such aid can start to flow.
President Bill Clinton phoned Mr Kravchuk last month to express
disappointment that the Ukrainian parliament voted for only partial
implementation of Start-1. But US officials were more encouraged this week
by Mr Kravchuk's decision to deactivate some of Ukraine's SS-24s.
Double trouble, Page 11
</TEXT>
