<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Inflation in France at 0.1% in November
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
French retail prices were virtually static last month with a rise of just
0.1 per cent, according to Insee, the state statistics institute. The
figures partly reflected the sluggish state of the French economy.
The negligible rise in November's prices means that French retail price
inflation has risen by a modest 2.2 per cent since the start of this year.
The retail sector has come under intense strain and manufacturers in some
sectors, notably food and clothing, have been forced to cut prices.
The price of private sector manufactured goods fell 0.2 per cent last month,
according to Insee, mainly due to the cut in clothing prices. But the cost
of unseasonal perishable products, notably fresh fruit and vegetables, rose
sharply.
Strains on the consumer sector were underlined by publication of a Paris
Chamber of Commerce and Industry study showing that retail sales fell in
November compared with October. Hypermarkets and supermarkets were worst
affected, with department stores mustering a slight rise.
However, the French franc strengthened again on further evidence of the
impact of France's economic rigour. The franc, which recently returned to
its old European exchange rate mechanism trading bands for the first time
since the summer currency crisis, rose to FFr3.4063 against the D-Mark from
FFr3.4079.
</TEXT>
