<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 93 / Yeltsin hint of new economic course
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Boris Yeltsin yesterday foreshadowed a shift in Russian economic
policy away from fighting inflation in favour of more emphasis on investment
and production.
The Russian leader said the large vote won by the neo-fascist Liberal
Democratic Party of Mr Vladimir Zhirinovsky was 'a vote against poverty' by
those on low incomes.
'Do not forget the poor, there are many of them,' Mr Yeltsin said while
touring a building exhibition.
Later, Mr Yeltsin told the presidential council of advisers he intended to
'co-operate constructively' with the new parliament - without specifying
with which parties he meant to work. Council members said the president
wanted the reforms to take on 'a more social orientation', Itar Tass news
agency reported.
Presidential aides said a struggle was going on last night over whether the
president should use a press conference today to say he is ready to work
with 'constructive' forces in the new parliament - but it is not clear
whether this term will include Mr Zhirinovsky's party, or only the four
reformist parties.
The Interfax news agency reported that Mr Zhirinovsky held a long
conversation on Monday night with Mr Nikolai Medvedev, Mr Yeltsin's head of
administration - a sign that Mr Yeltsin is anxious to explore all options.
The new parliament is unlikely to have a majority for either pro- or
anti-reform parties as there will be around 140 independent deputies.
However, it is likely the anti-reformers will be the largest single bloc -
and the signs were yesterday that they are trying to work together.
Mr Gennady Zyuganov, leader of the Communist party, the third largest bloc
in the lower house, said yesterday he was ready to work with any party which
'struggles for the integrity of our country, peace and well-being of every
family'. He said he did not believe the Liberal Democrats were a fascist
party, and said the formation of an anti-fascist front, proposed by Mr Yegor
Gaidar, the first deputy prime minister, would lead only to civil war.
Mr Yeltsin's comments on the poor came after an indication from Mr Gaidar
that he would consider moving the government's priorities away from fighting
inflation to increasing investment and raising production. This in turn
followed comments by Mr Viktor Chernomyrdin, the prime minister, that the
strategy of fighting inflation associated with Mr Gaidar had failed and that
he 'had better think again'.
Mr Alexander Shokhin, deputy prime minister in charge of foreign economic
relations, said yesterday many underutilised resources could be brought into
production without increasing inflation. 'That means of course choosing
which enterprises to support, rather than supporting all even if they are on
the verge of bankruptcy,' he said.
</TEXT>
