<PROFILE>_AN-DLUC5AF8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931221
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Survey of Sweden (16): Clear winner of the crisis - Profile:
Svenska Handelsbanken
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Svenska Handelsbanken is one of the clear winners of the Nordic banking
crisis. It has suffered much lower losses than its rivals and is the only
leading bank in Sweden, Norway or Finland which neither received nor sought
any form of state assistance.
The bank's reputation has clearly benefited, enabling it to pick up market
share. It also fares better than most of its rivals in terms of credit
rating and customer satisfaction. And yet, with clear signs that the worst
of the Swedish banking crisis is over and many competitor banks
recapitalised, it remains uncertain whether the bank will derive any
significant long-term commercial advantage from its performance.
Signs that Handelsbanken had turned the corner to better times have been
clear since the first quarter. By the nine-month stage, profits had reached
SKr1.39bn compared with a SKr883m loss in the same 1992 period. The
improvement can be attributed to a 30 per cent rise in profits before credit
losses to SKr6.67bn and to a 12 per cent fall in credit losses to SKr5.28bn.
Analysts are now predicting a full year profit of about SKr1.8-2bn, after
last year's SKr840m deficit.
So what did Handelsbanken do right, when so many other Nordic banks
foundered on the rocks of financial deregulation? In one sense, it simply
benefited from having weathered a crisis of its own in the early 1970s which
led to tighter credit control procedures. This meant that when the Swedish
financial market was deregulated in 1985, it did not chase new business as
aggressively as other banks, putting its emphasis on profitability, not
volume.
A significant result of the strategy was that Handelsbanken lent less to
property companies and therefore it suffered less from the collapse in
property values which lie at the heart of Sweden's banking crisis. Last
year, for example, real estate accounted for 60 per cent of the bank's
SKr8bn lending losses, compared with the Swedish average of 75 per cent.
The bank highlights two other reasons for its success. One is an emphasis on
competence and decision-making at branch level. 'If you look at the
financial crises in different western countries, you often see that some of
the worst credit decisions have been taken by banks without local
knowledge,' says Mr Arne Martensson, the bank's chief executive
The other is a relentless drive to cut costs. Handelsbanken already claims
to have the lowest cost base of any Nordic bank, because it has held down
staff numbers even though it has maintained a large number of branches as
part of its emphasis on local market expertise. Far from being complacent
about its market position, it promises further cost-cutting to maintain its
competitive edge.
The question now is whether Handelsbanken will benefit from the goodwill
associated with its performance. It has certainly gained market share in the
past three years - its share of total lending among Swedish banks rose from
16.5 per cent to 17.3 per cent between 1990 and 1992, while its share of
total deposits increased to 15.3 per cent from 13.9 per cent.
Making further gains, however, will be harder, as Mr Martensson
acknowledges, now that the bank's competitors are showing clear signs of
recovering their strength. SE Banken has rebuilt it balance sheet with a
SKr5.3bn rights issue, while state-owned Nordbanken, stripped of the bulk of
its bad loans, has rebounded strongly into profit. Mr Martensson says
bluntly that the state gave Nordbanken too much support to the clear
competitive disadvantage of the country's other banks.
One sign that Handelsbanken is determined not to lose out in the battle for
business as the Swedish economy recovers was its decision to launch a
SKr2.7bn rights issue during the autumn. This lifted its capital adequacy
ratio to 12.4 per cent, far higher than the 9.4 per cent level it reached in
1989 when bank profits were at a peak.
Part of the reason the bank wanted such a strong balance sheet was to
improve its credit rating, but it also wanted funds to help build up its
bank network throughout the Nordic region.
It already has seven branches in Norway, following the acquisition of Oslo
Handelsbanken in 1990 and Stavanger Bank in 1991, and it has started up
operations in Denmark and Finland.
'Our ambition is to build up the type of operation which we have in Sweden
in other Nordic countries,' says Mr Martensson.
Here, too, the bank is unlikely to have things all its own way because SE
Banken has recently announced plans to set up offices in Oslo and Helsinki.
But Mr Martensson believes Handelsbanken has gained a head start on its
rivals, partly because it was able to exploit the banking crises in both
Norway and Finland to get an earlier foothold on better terms.
The bank is also aiming to build up its life insurance business in Sweden.
It is already the country's fifth-largest life insurer with a 7 per cent
market share.
Given that Handelsbanken is also seeking to develop its banking operations
in Sweden, it came as some surprise when it pulled out of the bidding for
Gota Bank, the state-owned bank, earlier this month. Mr Martensson said the
price being sought by the government was 'far too high' and the bank would
be risking its credit rating and international competitiveness if it went
ahead with the purchase.
</TEXT>
<XX>
