<PROFILE>_AN-DLUC5AF7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931221
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Survey of Sweden (14): Clear evidence of a turnround - The
Banking Sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Swedish banks are emerging from crisis as rapidly as they plunged into it.
The doom-laden atmosphere of the early part of the year, when record losses
were being unveiled and banks were falling over each other in the queue for
state hand-outs, has rapidly given way to a mood of optimism. The feeling is
not just that the worst is over but that the path to recovery is firmly
entrenched.
Much-improved results are the clearest evidence of the turnround and these,
together with the buoyant stock market, have enabled banks to recapitalise
by turning to their shareholders and other institutions, rather than relying
on the state.
All three banks which applied for state aid at the start of the year -
Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken, Foreningsbanken, and Swedbank - had withdrawn
their requests by the year-end.
The government has reason to congratulate itself over developments, even if
the main reason for the upturn is the sharp lowering of interest rates which
has followed the humiliating decision to float the krona in November 1992.
The measures the government took to tackle the crisis - providing a blanket
safety net for the entire banking system, encouraging banks to dig their own
way out of trouble, using the 'bad bank' formula for problem loans - have
proved effective both in maintaining confidence and securing the recovery.
Yet the process has not been without controversy. Nordbanken, the first and
biggest casualty of the crisis, has almost certainly been treated too
generously by the state to the distortion of wider competition. After nine
months it was Sweden's most profitable bank with a SKr2.5bn operating profit
 -quite a turnround on the SKr16bn record-breaking loss it recorded for the
whole of 1992.
Now Nordbanken is to be slung together with Gota Bank to create Sweden's
biggest bank in terms of market share with a likely privatisation of the
combined entity in 1995. Although presented as the best solution for the
taxpayer, it represents something of a defeat for the government's earlier
hopes of getting a significant foreign presence into the market to bolster
competition.
The danger is that the bank crisis will pass in Sweden without a significant
increase in the market competition, even though more domestic players -
including insurance groups - are entering the field.
Now that Gota's problems have been resolved, at a total cost of SKr30bn, the
government's biggest banking crisis outlays are behind it. So far, the state
has provided a total of SKr92.1bn in support, by way of cash infusions,
equity, loans and guarantees, although only SKr71.3bn of the total has
actually been paid out. One estimate is that the net outlay will be about
SKr50bn once the government has recouped funds from Nordbanken's
privatisation and the sale of assets within the bad banks.
So is the crisis over? Not if the size of the credit losses and problem
loans still being reported is anything to go by. In the first half of this
year, credit losses amounted to SKr39bn, compared with SKr74bn in the whole
of 1992. The trend should be lower in the second half, but it is clear that
full-year losses are going to be in the region of SKr60-65bn.
'Credit losses will still be above normal levels in both 1994 and 1995,'
warns Mr Peter Mansson, financial analyst at ABB Aros Securities in
Stockholm.
Another sign that the market is still thought to be unstable is the fact
that the blanket guarantee which the government was forced to place under
the entire banking system in late 1992 is still in place, and there are no
signs of its early removal.
One measurement shows why this is the case: there is still an estimated
SKr100bn of problem loans in the Swedish banking system, while banks'
primary capital at the end of the third quarter amounted to only SKr67bn.
Even allowing for the recapitalisation measures in the final three months,
there is still a shortfall.
If interest rates went back up again, things could certainly go wrong. But
even if they did, the big groups are now far better placed to withstand
heavy losses without breaching the 8 per cent minimum capital adequacy
level. Capital adequacy ratios at both SE Banken and Svenska Handelsbanken
are now above 12 per cent after they raised SKr5.3bn and SKr2.7bn
respectively in rights issues during the autumn.
Swedbank, the Nordic region's biggest bank in asset terms, will have capital
cover of more than 10 per cent if plans to strengthen its capital base by
SKr8bn are fully implemented.
The recovery undoubtedly leaves a more limited role for the bank support
authority, the Bankstodsnamnden, which was only formally set up in May. Its
main task will be to take care of Nordbanken; its bad bank, Securum; and
Gota's bad bank, Retriva. In general, the authority will act more as a
holding company than be active and 'hands-on' in its approach.
The 10-15 years envisaged for the sell-off of assets within Securum and
Retriva indicate that the legacy of the banking crisis will last into the
next century. The fall-out has also led to the scrutiny of SKr37.8bn of
loans for evidence of wrong-doing and, in some cases, individual board
directors may be held to account for the decisions which they took.
One obvious worry is that with many of Sweden's banks so strongly
recapitalised, the whole cycle of misery will simply repeat itself in a few
years as the leading groups make another grab for market share. The danger
is the greater for the fact that Sweden has a small domestic market, which
may force banks to push into areas or countries with which they are
unfamiliar.
For the moment most believe that lessons have been learned and that credit
control procedures have been tightened. 'Banks are much more cautious now
and I don't believe they will start recklessly chasing volumes again,' says
Mr Claes Norgren, head of the country's finance inspection board.
Not everyone takes this view, and they back their case by saying that many
of the people who took the decisions which brought disaster last time round
are still in place.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken.
    Foreningsbanken.
    Swedbank.
    Nordbanken.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SEZ  Sweden, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6081 Foreign Banking and Branches and Agencies.
</IN>
