<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Survey of Sweden (12): Rivals gathering strength - Motor
industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The drama of Volvo's failed plan to merge with France's Renault and -
earlier - the launch of a new car billed as a make-or-break model for Saab
has evoked much worried concern in Sweden this year about the future of the
country's motor industry.
A close look behind the headlines suggests, however, that both Volvo and
Saab are in positions of gathering strength, at least in the short to medium
term.
In contrast to the formidable structural problems facing such European
giants as Volkswagen, Fiat and Mercedes, both Swedish companies have already
been through a painful process of rationalisation and are beginning to reap
the benefits.
'I think both Saab and Volvo are in rather good industrial shape at the
moment,' was the somewhat surprising remark of a Volvo car company executive
in the aftermath of the Renault merger collapse.
Not that there is any complacency in the two western cities of Gothenburg
and Trollhaten, where Volvo and Saab have their respective headquarters and
main plants.
In the long term, a big question mark hangs over Volvo's strategy now that
the merger with Renault is off. Volvo readily acknowledges that it needs a
partner to ensure its long-term stability in a world motor industry carrying
heavy overcapacity.
It is worried that Renault will gradually reverse out of their
three-year-old alliance after the snub of rejection delivered by Volvo
senior management and its shareholders.
Saab Automobile, which is jointly owned by General Motors of the US and
Sweden's Saab-Scania group, also has a long way to go to prove its long-term
viability after five successive years of losses and tumbling sales.
But for the time being the graph is pointing up for both the long-time
rivals, despite the toughest recession for years in the wider European
market and especially at home, where annual car sales have plummeted from
340,000 in 1988 to about 125,000 this year.
Indeed, a surge back into profits at Volvo in recent months was one of the
factors cited by those who opposed the merger with Renault, which has
suffered sharp reverses in profitability this year.
In the first nine months, the Volvo group reported a SKr2bn improvement in
operating profits, swinging from a SKr1.52bn loss in the same period in 1992
to a Skr445m profit.
Both the car and truck divisions were profitable, with the long-running
trend of falling unit sales shifted back to growth, albeit very small. Car
sales were up to 229,400 from 228,900.
In the car operations, Volvo attributes a good deal of this turnaround to a
tough programme of restructuring. In response to mounting losses in the
early 1990s, Volvo is shutting two of its three Swedish plants and by 1995
will have cut 15,000 staff from the workforce.
Meanwhile, efficiency has been sharply improved, with the number of hours
taken to make a vehicle tumbling from 70 to 40.
At Saab, which ran up losses totalling SKr10bn over the past four years,
there is a similar story. Losses are down sharply this year and the company
expects to return to the black in 1994 for the first time since 1988.
If so, it will be the result of a severe restructuring that required the
injection of SKr8bn in new capital from GM and Saab-Scania.
Production has been concentrated in three plants and the workforce halved to
about 7,300. Production time for the new 900 model, launched in July, is
down to about 30 hours compared with figures as high as 110 hours a few
years ago. Sales, which have slumped from 109,500 in 1989 to 75,000 this
year, have begun to turn around.
The company projects sales of the 9000 and 900 to total 87,000 next year,
ahead of the break-even level of 80,000.
Both Saab and Volvo, which export the big majority of their cars, are
benefiting strongly from the windfall effects of a 30 per cent fall in the
value of the Swedish krona since last year. Both have narrow model ranges
limited to the middle and upper market tiers. Their traditional competitive
advantages of safety and environmental friendliness are fast being caught up
by their competitors. Volvo has taken a dangerous leap in the dark by
tearing up the Renault merger plan.
The two rivals still have to prove that Sweden can be a competitive location
for vehicle making in the long term. But the progress they have made in 1993
has at least set them up with a chance of success.
</TEXT>
